{[%evp 0,7,12,12,21,21,21,21,21,18] In this repertoire the lines will be
initially equal but if you know the plans well, you will have very good
chances to obtain an advantage.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 (2... Nf6 {One big
advantage of this repertoire is that we don't have to deal with the Petrov!} 3.
Nc3 {and Black will have to transpose to our main line with 3...Nb8-c6 or to
the Philidor with 3...d7-d6} Nc6 (3... d6 4. d4 {see Philidor.}) 4. Bb5 {
see Spanish Four Knights.}) 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] This is a good
system for White which doesn't have a lot of theory. More important in this
line is understanding all the different ideas. Black will need to develop the
bishop to either the d6--square, the c5-square or the b4-square. We will
analyse all the typical strategies against these moves. Our main idea here is
to take the c6-knight quickly.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "SPANISH FOUR KNIGHTS 4.Bb4/Bc"]
[Black "FULL THEORY"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C49"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "29"]
[EventDate "2021.10.09"]

{[%evp 0,21,28,28,38,43,9,4,10,5,5,6,14,25,-8,20,19,21,28,3,1,4,-4,-3] Here we
will have a look at all the different dark-squared bishop moves. The arising
structure will be almost always the same so the ideas we'll see apply
everywhere.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Bb4 $1 {
This is the best move in my opinion. It is also the most played move.} (4...
Bd6 $5 {is also playable, but is bit strange looking. Here we are not in a
hurry to take the c6-knight because Black will have to force the matter with ..
.a7-a6 rather sooner than later.} 5. d3 O-O 6. O-O $1 Re8 (6... Ne7 $6 {
We are not afraid of this move because now we can strike in the centre and
claim the advantage.} 7. d4 $14 (7. Bc4 $1 {might even be stronger.} Ng6 8. d4
$14)) 7. h3 a6 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Ne2 {And again, our typical non-forcing plan.
We start preparing the f2-f4 break. As always in this repertoire there is no
theory. Let's check some sample lines.} c5 10. b3 $1 (10. Nh2 $6 c4 $15 {
is a typical source of counterplay for Black. Don't allow this!}) 10... Nd7 (
10... Be6 11. Bb2 {Developing the c1-bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal is something
we might consider. The b2-bishop can assist the attack on the Black king.} Nd7
12. Nh2 Nf8 13. f4 exf4 14. Nxf4 Ng6 15. Nxe6 (15. Nh5 $5) 15... Rxe6 16. Ng4
a5 17. Qf3 Qd7 18. a4 $16 {We have successfully stopped Black's counterplay on
the queenside while our pieces are perfectly placed to eye the Black king.
White is for choice here.}) 11. Nh2 (11. a4 $5 $14) 11... Nf8 12. f4 exf4 13.
Bxf4 Bxf4 (13... Ng6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Kh1 (15. Qd2 Rxe4 $19 {Watch out for
these tactical motives!}) 15... Ne5 16. Qe1 Be6 17. Qf2 f6 18. Nf3 b6 19. Nxe5
fxe5 {[%csl Re5] The e5-pawn is weak, we'll regroup our pieces to start
attacking it.} (19... Qxe5 20. Qf4 $1 $14 {The endgames in this structure
favour White. Black doesn't have constructive ideas on the queenside while
White will soon start a minority attack on the kingside!}) 20. Qg3 Rf8 21. Ng1
$16 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg1f3]}) 14. Nxf4 Bd7 15. Kh1 a5 16. a4 Ne6 17. Nd5 Bc6
18. Ne3 Nd4 {[%csl Rd4,Ge3] is very important. To fight against a knight on
the d4-square we put a knight on the e3-square. The e3-knight is stronger than
it counterpart on the d4-square!!} 19. Nf3 Bd7 20. Nxd4 cxd4 21. Nf5 Bxf5 22.
Rxf5 $16 {with an endgame once more. White is ready to start pushing pawns on
the kingside after doubling all the heavy pieces on the f-file. We can imagine
forcing Black to continue with ...f7-f6 when we can create a protected passed
pawn on the f-file with pushing the g2-pawn all the way to the g5-square.}) (
4... Bc5 $5 {This is a playable move, although not the best. Now we should
take the c6-knight immediately, forcing Black to take back with the d-pawn.} 5.
Bxc6 $1 dxc6 6. d3 {We can't take the poisoned e5-pawn. This is basically the
last move you need to remember. From here out it's all plans! We'll analyze
some sample lines.} O-O (6... Qe7 7. h3 O-O 8. O-O Bd7 9. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Gf3h2,
Gf2f4,Gg1h1]} b5 {is premature. We can continue with the standard plan, but we
can also try to exploit this.} 10. a4 $1 $16 (10. Kh1 {There's nothing wrong
with the normal set-up.} a5 11. Nh2 a4 12. f4 exf4 13. Nxf4 a3 14. b3 Bd4 15.
Rb1 $16 {Black was able to push some pawns, but still doesn't really have a
target.}) 10... a5 11. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Ra5] Eyeing the a5-weakness. Black is
basically forced to push b5-b4 but then there is no more hope for counterplay.}
b4 (11... Bb6 12. Bc3 $1 $16 {[%csl Re5] and White picks up a pawn.} (12. Qe1
$1 {Not necessary here because 12.Bc3 wins a pawn, but it is an instructive
idea!. We increase the pressure on the a5-pawn so Black now really is forced
to push the b-pawn.} b4 13. b3 $16)) 12. Ng3 $16) (6... Bg4 $6 7. h3 Bxf3 8.
Qxf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Ne2 a5 11. a4 $1 Bd6 12. Ng3 c5 13. b3 $16) 7. O-O Bg4
$6 {is what everybody plays, but it's not good!} (7... Bd6 8. h3 $1 {[%cal
Gc3e2,Gf3d2,Gf3h2,Gf2f4]} Re8 9. Ne2 Nd7 10. Nd2 Nf8 11. Nc4 Ne6 12. b3 (12. a4
$1 $14) 12... c5 13. a4 Nd4 (13... f6 14. f4 exf4 15. Bxf4 Bxf4 16. Nxf4 Nd4
17. Ne3 Be6 (17... f5 {doesn't work due to tactical reasons.} 18. c3 $16) 18.
Kh1 Bf7 19. Qd2 Qd7 20. g4 Rad8 21. Qg2 $17) 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. f4 exf4 16. Nxd6
Qxd6 17. Bxf4 Qe7 18. Qh5 Be6 19. Rf3 c5 20. Raf1 f6 21. Rg3 $16 {and Black is
under pressure.}) 8. h3 Bh5 9. Kh1 $1 {We are slowly preparing g2-g4!} Re8 10.
Qe2 $1 {protecting f2 and preparing Rg1} (10. Be3 $1 $14 {also quite good} Bxe3
11. fxe3 $16) 10... a5 11. a4 $1 Qd7 12. Rg1 Bb4 13. Nd1 h6 14. g4 Bg6 15. Ne3
$16) 5. O-O O-O (5... Bxc3 $6 6. bxc3 Nxe4 7. Qe2 $16 Nd6 8. Bxc6 dxc6 9. Qxe5+
Kf8 10. d3 $16 {[%csl Rf8]}) 6. Bxc6 $1 dxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 {does not work out
here for Black. This is one of the only lines you have to study by heart.} 7.
Nxe5 $1 Re8 8. Nd3 Bxc3 9. dxc3 Nxe4 {and we have reached a position that
appears equal, but the opposite is true!} 10. Re1 d5 $6 {x c7} (10... d6 11. f3
Nf6 12. Bg5 $14 {sets up an annoying pin that will be realy hard to break.} Be6
13. Qd2 h6 14. Bh4 Rb8 15. b3 c5 16. c4 g5 {breaks the pin, but leaves Black
with a weak king.} 17. Bf2 $16) (10... h6 {Black tries to prevent Bg5 so he
can safely retreat the e4-knight with an equal position.} 11. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 12.
Qg4+ Ng5 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. h4 $16) 11. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rc7] and Black will
always have trouble with the weak c7-pawn.} Ba6 12. Qg4 Bc8 13. Qf3 $16) 7. d3
{And once more we have reached our typical pawn structure. Also once more from
here it's all plans and no theory. We'll analyze the typical ideas in some
sample lines. Our main idea is to break open the position with f2-f4. We
prepare this break with Nc3-e2, h2-h3, Nf3-h2 and eventually f2-f4 will follow.
On the queenside, we can play b2-b3 and a2-a4 to stop Black from creating
something there. The c1-bishop is perfectly placed to support the f2-f4 break
and can develop in one go with Bxf4. Developing to the a1-h8 is also on the
agenda.} Re8 (7... Bxc3 {This appears to be a mistake, our dark-squared will
become very strong now. We can continue in several ways: stick to the plan and
go for the f2-f4 break or fix the queenside with a2-a4 and c3-c4.} 8. bxc3 Bg4
(8... Nd7 9. a4 Re8 10. c4 $14 Nc5 11. Bb2 Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 (12... Bh5 13. g4
$18 {wins a pawn.}) 13. Qxf3 Ne6 14. Qe3 Nd4 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. Qg3 $16 {
[%cal Gf2f4]}) (8... Re8 9. h3 (9. a4 $14) 9... h6 10. Nh2 c5 11. c4 Qd6 12.
Be3 b6 13. f4 $18 exf4 14. Bxf4 Qd4+ 15. Kh1 Be6 16. Bxc7 $18) 9. h3 Bh5 10.
Kh1 $1 {Preparing Rf1-g1 to play g2-g4 shutting Black's light-squared bishop
down.} c5 11. c4 Re8 12. Rg1 Qd7 13. g4 Bg6 14. a4 $16 Rad8 15. Qe2 (15. Rg3
Nxe4 $19 {Always be careful not to allow these tactics.}) 15... Qc6 16. Nh4 $16
(16. Bb2 $16)) (7... Bd6 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black wants to grab some space with ...
c6-c5.} 8. Ne2 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gf3h2,Gf2f4]} c5 (8... Re8 9. h3 (9. Ng3 $6 {
is not what we want because although the knight is sitting pretty on the
g3-square, it's not supporting our main plan: the f2-f4 break}) 9... Bd7 10.
Nh2 Qe7 11. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] simple as that.} exf4 12. Bxf4 Bxf4 13. Nxf4 c5
14. b3 $1 {[%cal Rc5c4]} Bc6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5]} 15. Qd2 Rad8 16. Qf2 Nd7 17.
Ng4 Ne5 18. Ne3 g6 19. a4 $16 {killing all counterplay.} (19. Qg3 $16 {[%cal
Gf1f2,Ga1f1,Gf4h5,Ge3f5]})) 9. a4 $14 (9. Nd2 $14) 9... Bg4 10. Ng3 $1 {
[%cal Gh2h3]} Nh5 11. h3 $1 Nxg3 12. fxg3 Be6 13. b3 $1 f6 14. Nh4 $14 {
[%cal Gg3g4]}) (7... Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. Kh1 {Again this idea, we prepare g2-g4.}
Re8 10. Rg1 Bd6 11. g4 Bg6 12. Bg5 $16 (12. Be3 $16)) (7... Nd7 8. Ne2 (8. h3
$5) 8... Re8 (8... f6 9. Nd2 Re8 10. Nc4 $14) 9. h3 Nf8 10. Nh2 Ng6 11. Kh1 Bd6
12. f4 exf4 13. Nxf4 Bxf4 14. Bxf4 Nxf4 15. Rxf4 Qd4 16. Rb1 Be6 17. b3 f6 18.
Qf3 a5 19. Rf1 $16) 8. Ne2 Bd6 (8... Bg4 9. Ng3 Nh5 10. h3 Nxg3 11. fxg3 $16) (
8... Bf8 9. h3 c5 (9... Nd7 10. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] Here the fianchetto plan also
works well.} c5 11. Bb2 (11. a4 {slow, but also good.}) 11... f6 12. Nd2 $16)
10. b3 a5 11. a4 Nd7 12. Nd2 $1 (12. Nh2 $1) (12. Kh1 $1) 12... b6 13. Nc4 f6
14. Bb2 Ba6 15. Ne3 $16) 9. h3 Nd7 (9... Nh5 10. Ng3 Nf4 11. d4 exd4 (11... f6
12. c3 $16) 12. e5 $16) 10. Nh2 c5 11. b3 Nf8 12. Qe1 Ne6 13. f4 exf4 14. Nxf4
Bf8 15. a4 $14 {with a typical position for this opening line. White is
enjoying easy play with clear plans while Black doesn't have a clear target.
We're happy here!} *

