{[%evp 0,31,16,28,75,85,82,80,96,57,67,52,66,59,30,34,59,34,54,49,55,43,42,18,
17,-3,52,49,60,19,44,62,82,56]} 1. e4 d6 {This is the best move order to play
the Philidor.} (1... e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {and Black is more or less forced to
take on d4, other lines are just bad.} Nd7 $6 {Does not work here because
White is not forced to play 4.Nb1-c3. Instead we can get more active!} (3... f5
$2 4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 6. Neg5 h6 7. Nf7 $3 Kxf7 8. Nxe5+ $18) (3... Nc6 4.
Bb5 $1 exd4 5. Qxd4 Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nc3 $14) (3... Bg4 4. dxe5 $1 {follows
a famous Morphy game!} Bxf3 (4... Nc6 5. Bb5 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 dxe5 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8.
Nd2 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7]}) 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4 Nf6 7. Qb3 Qe7 8. Nc3 c6 9.
Bg5 b5 10. Nxb5 cxb5 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 12. O-O-O Rd8 13. Rxd7 Rxd7 14. Rd1 Qe6 15.
Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Qb8+ Nxb8 17. Rd8#) (3... Nf6 4. dxe5 Nxe4 5. Qd5 Nc5 6. Bg5 Qd7
7. Nc3 $16 {and Black lacks coordination.}) (3... exd4 $5 {is how Black should
handle the Philidor after starting with 1...e7-e5. Here we get a space
advantage and that will be enough to claim the upper hand.} 4. Nxd4 (4. Qxd4 $5
{also is interesting.} Nc6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bd7 (5... Nc6 6. Qd3 $5 $14 Be7 7.
Bf4) 6. Bg5 Nc6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O $14) 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8.
Bg5 Be7 9. O-O-O O-O 10. Rhe1 $14) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Be2 $1 {is the
easiest solution, we're going to enjoy a space advantage.} O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Bf4
Re8 9. Re1 $14 Bf8 10. Bf1 Nbd7 11. Qd2 $14) 4. Bc4 $1 c6 (4... Be7 $2 {
is already losing.} 5. dxe5 {Note that we almost never play this move unless
we have a tactical motive.} Nxe5 (5... dxe5 6. Qd5 $16 {[%csl Re5,Rf7]}) 6.
Nxe5 dxe5 7. Qh5 $16 {[%csl Re5,Rf7]}) 5. O-O Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5 Bxg5 8.
Qh5 Qe7 9. Qxg5 Qxg5 (9... Ngf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. f3 $14) 10. Bxg5 Ngf6 11. f3
$14 {and White is enjoying the pair of bishops with a risk-free advantage.} Nb6
12. Bb3 O-O 13. a4 a5 14. Be3 Nbd7 15. Nd2 $14) 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 $1
Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 (5... c6 $4 {Black mixed things up with the move order!} 6.
dxe5 $1 $18 Nxe5 (6... dxe5 7. Ng5 $18) 7. Nxe5 dxe5 8. Bxf7+ Ke7 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8
10. f3 $18 {with a clear pawn up.}) (5... exd4 $6 6. Qxd4 $1 {now, taking with
the queen is even better because there is no ...Nc6 at all!} Be7 (6... c6 7. a4
$14) 7. Bf4 O-O 8. O-O-O $16 (8. O-O $14) 8... Nb6 9. Bb3 $16) 6. O-O O-O (6...
c6 $5 {Let's check some ideas where Black doesn't castle. Spoiler alert: they
don't work.} 7. a4 Qc7 8. Re1 h6 9. h3 (9. a5 $5 {this is also interesting.
We're postponing h3 so we don't give a target for Black's potential attack. In
the meantime, we're grabbing space on the queenside.} O-O (9... Nf8 10. Nh4 $16
g5 11. dxe5 $1 dxe5 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 $16 {We have the bishop pair, the
better pawn structure and the better pieces. Black is not in great shape here.}
) 10. h3 $14) 9... Nf8 (9... g5 10. a5 $1 Nf8 11. b4 Ng6 (11... g4 12. hxg4
Bxg4 13. Qd3 $1 {breaking the pin.} Bxf3 14. Qxf3 exd4 15. Ne2 $18) 12. b5 $1
$16 g4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. a6 $1 Bxf3 (14... bxa6 15. Rxa6 $16) 15. axb7 Qxb7 16.
Qxf3 exd4 17. e5 Nxe5 18. Rxe5 dxe5 19. bxc6 Qc8 20. Nd5 $18 {is crushing.})
10. Nh4 $1 $16 g5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nf5 $16) 7. a4 $5 {This seems to be the
most accurate move order though there's nothing wrong with starting with 7.
Rf1-e3 or 7.h2-h3} c6 (7... a6 8. h3 $1 (8. a5 $5 $14) 8... b6 9. Be3 $5 {
We wait for Black to play Bc8-b7 after which we continue with d4-d5, closing
down the b7-bishop.} (9. Re1 $14) 9... Bb7 (9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Bb7 11. Nf5 $3
$16 (11. f3 $16)) 10. d5 $1 {[%csl Rb7]} Ne8 $5 (10... c6 $6 11. dxc6 Bxc6 12.
Qd3 $3 $16 {is an important concept to remember. White has consolidated and
has everything protected. Later we can start attacking the weak d6-pawn.} Qc7
13. Rfd1 Qb7 (13... Bb7 14. Nd2 $16 Rfd8 15. Nf1 Nc5 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. Qe2 Rd4
18. Ne3 $18) 14. Nd2 $16 Nc5 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Bd5 $3 Rfd8 17. Nc4 $18) (10...
Nc5 11. Nd2 $16) 11. Kh2 $3 {is an amazing concept found by the engines. White
is stopping all Black counterplay with g2-g4 next.} g6 (11... f5 $2 12. exf5
$16) 12. Bh6 Ng7 13. g4 $3 $16 Kh8 14. Rg1 $3 $16 {is a nice prophylactic move.
} Nf6 15. Qe2 Ng8 $1 (15... Qd7 16. Rg3 $16 c6 17. dxc6 Qxc6 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19.
Bxd5 Qc7 20. Bb3 $16) 16. Bd2 f5 17. gxf5 gxf5 18. exf5 $1 (18. Rg2 $1 $16 f4
19. Rag1 Bf6 20. Ng5 $16) 18... Nxf5 19. Rg2 Nf6 20. Rag1 $16 {With a lot of
activity. Note that the b7-bishop has great difficulties joining the game.}) 8.
h3 $1 b6 (8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 d5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 dxc4 12. Nd6 Be6 (12...
Bxd6 13. exd6 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc1f4] The d6-pawn will be a great asset of
which Black can't get easily rid off.}) 13. Ra3 $16) (8... h6 9. Re1 Qc7 10.
Be3 {transposes.}) (8... Qc7 9. Re1 h6 10. Be3 Re8 11. a5 $16) 9. Re1 a6 10.
Be3 Bb7 (10... Rb8 11. Ba2 $1 {anticipating Black's ...b6-b5-idea.} b5 (11...
Bb7 12. dxe5 dxe5 (12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. g4 $3 (15. Red1
$16) 15... h6 16. Red1 $16 Bc7 17. f3 Rfd8 18. Kf2 $16) 13. Nh4 g6 14. Nf3 $16)
12. axb5 axb5 13. b4 $1 Qc7 14. Bb3 $14 (14. Qd2 $14) 14... Nb6 15. Qd3 h6 16.
dxe5 (16. Ra2 $16) 16... dxe5 17. Bc5 $3 $16) (10... h6 11. Nh4 $3 $16 (11.
dxe5 $5 dxe5 12. Nh4 $16)) (10... Qc7 11. Nh4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Ne5 13. Ba2 $14)
11. dxe5 $1 {You should be extremely careful playing this type of move because
it is a strategic mistake. It releases the tension in the centre, frees up the
c5-square for the e7-bishop or the d7-knight, and makes it easier for Black to
adjust plans because the pawn structure is now fixed. So you should play this
type of move only when there's concrete play, which, luckily for us, is the
case here. Ideas will almost always be combined with Nf3-h4 or Nf3-g5.} dxe5
12. Nh4 $3 {[%cal Gh4f5]} g6 (12... Nxe4 $2 13. Nxe4 Bxh4 14. Qg4 Kh8 15. Nd6
$18 Nf6 16. Nxf7+ Rxf7 17. Qxh4) 13. Nf3 $1 (13. Ba2 $1 $16) 13... b5 14. Ba2
$16 b4 15. Nb1 Nxe4 16. Bh6 $18 *

