{[%evp 0,65,21,21,18,18,18,18,18,18,37,30,9,8,6,6,33,33,33,20,34,8,8,-3,17,35,
58,44,92,81,88,70,70,31,76,60,67,66,115,118,121,128,119,111,155,151,158,194,
201,205,209,216,223,232,226,242,237,250,368,384,661,698,689,564,29987,29988,
29989,29990] notes by Alexakis Dimitris} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bb5
Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Bxc3 $2 {Now white has a clear and solid
advantage!} 8. bxc3 Re8 9. h3 h6 10. Nh2 Qd6 11. Kh1 (11. f4 $5 exf4 12. Bxf4
Qc5+ 13. Kh1 Qxc3 14. Bxc7 (14. Qf3 Be6 15. Bxh6 gxh6 16. Qxf6 Qxf6 17. Rxf6
Kg7)) 11... g5 $5 {Even though the computer doesn't agree with this move, it
is definitely a very sensible choice because after f4 only white can create
good play} 12. h4 Nh7 13. Qh5 (13. g3 $5 Bh3 (13... f5 14. Qh5 Re7 15. exf5
Bxf5 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Bxg5 Rg7 18. Bh6 Rf7 19. Rae1) 14. Rg1) 13... Qg6 $2 (
13... Re6 $1 {That was the variation i was seeing where I would be better but
black would be very active and a bit dangerous} 14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Bxg5 Nxg5 16.
Qxg5+ Rg6 17. Qe3 Be6 18. f4 exf4 19. Qxf4) 14. Qxg6+ fxg6 15. hxg5 hxg5 (15...
Nxg5 16. f4 exf4 17. Bxf4 {[%csl Yc7,Yg5,Yh6]} Re7 18. Bxg5 (18. c4 {White
could keep the bishop because black is wide-open} Nf7 19. Bd2) 18... hxg5 {
White is more or less a pawn up}) 16. g4 $1 {Fixάρισμα!} b5 $2 (16... c5
17. c4 Bd7 18. a4 a5 19. Kg2 Re7 20. Kg3 Rf8 21. f3 b6 22. Rh1 Ref7 23. Bb2 Re8
24. Nf1 Ref8 25. Nd2 Re8 26. Rh3 Kg7 27. Nb1 Kf6 28. Nc3 Ke6 29. Rh6 Rg8 30.
Rah1 Nf8 31. Bc1 {[%csl Yg5]}) 17. Be3 {[%csl Yc5]} a6 18. Kg2 Kg7 19. Kg3 Bd7
20. Rh1 $1 (20. Nf3 Nf6 21. Nh2) 20... a5 21. a3 Ra6 22. Nf3 Nf6 23. Bxg5 Nxg4
24. Rh4 Nf6 25. Bxf6+ Kxf6 26. Rh7 Rd8 27. d4 exd4 28. cxd4 c5 29. d5 c6 30.
e5+ Kf5 31. Re1 g5 32. Rf7+ Kg6 33. e6 1-0

