{[%evp 0,21,28,28,38,43,9,4,10,5,5,6,14,25,-8,20,19,21,28,3,1,4,-4,-3]} 1. e4
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Nd4 $5 {This is playable and an
entirely different story. Here we're not getting our typical structure and
Black can get easy play if we don't know what we're doing. Luckily for us, I
offer three lines that give White practical chances.} (4... d6 $6 {is too
passive and we're already better after} 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bd7 7. Nxc6 $1 bxc6
{with two good options.} (7... Bxc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O $14) 8. Ba4 $16 (8.
Bc4 $16)) 5. O-O (5. Nxd4 $5 {This basically forces a draw.} exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7.
exf6 Qxf6 (7... cxd2+ $4 8. Bxd2 Qxf6 9. O-O $16 {black is almost lost here..
because he cannot castle!} Be7 10. Bc3 Qb6 11. Re1 $3 Qxb5 12. Qg4 $3 $18 d5 (
12... Rg8 13. Rxe7+ Kxe7 14. Re1+ Kd6 (14... Kf8 15. Qe4 {and checkmate}) (
14... Kd8 15. Bf6+ gxf6 16. Qxg8#) 15. a4 $3 Qd5 16. Rd1 $18) 13. Qxg7 Rf8 14.
Bf6 Be6 15. Rxe6) 8. dxc3 Bc5 (8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 d6 11. Re1 $14) 9.
Qe2+ Qe6 10. O-O Qxe2 11. Bxe2 d5 12. Bf4 c6 13. Bd3 $11 {with a completely
equal endgame.}) (5. Be2 {is also interesting and playable and actually has
some historic value. It has been played by old masters like Alekhine and
Maroczy.} Nxf3+ {is what they usually do.} (5... Nxe2 6. Qxe2 d6 7. d4 $14 {
with a small advantage due to our centre.}) 6. Bxf3 Bc5 (6... Bb4 7. a3 (7. d4
$14 {is also promising.}) 7... Bxc3 8. dxc3 d6 9. c4 Be6 10. b3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,
Gf3] and White has the upper hand with the bishop pair.}) 7. Na4 $1 {is the
strongest, we're going to set up a Maroczy bind.} (7. d3 {We wait with
castling and give Black a chance to make a mistake.} d6 $6 (7... a6 {keeps
more options open for Black.} 8. g4 $1 $11 {is interesting!}) 8. Na4 $1 {
and White will enjoy the advantage of the bishop pair.}) 7... Be7 8. c4 $14 {
[%cal Gd2d4]}) 5... Nxb5 (5... c6 6. Bd3 Nxf3+ (6... d6 $2 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Ne2
$14 c5 (8... d5 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Re1 Be7 11. h3 Qd8 (11... O-O 12. Nxd4 $18)
12. Bc4 O-O 13. d3 $16) 9. c3 dxc3 10. dxc3 $16) 7. Qxf3 d6 {and White has
several good ideas.} 8. Be2 (8. Bc4 $5 b5 9. Bb3 Be7 10. d3 O-O 11. h3 {
we are slowly preparing f4 !} a5 12. a4 b4 13. Ne2 Be6 14. Ng3 $5 Bxb3 15. cxb3
$16) (8. a4 $5 Be6 9. Be2 Be7 10. Qg3 O-O 11. d3 Nd7 12. Bg4 $14) 8... Be7 9.
Qg3 O-O 10. d3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 6. Nxb5 c6 7. Nc3 d6 8. d4 Qc7 9. Bg5 Be7
10. a4 $1 {stopping ...b7-b5 which is a typical idea in these Philidor-like
positions.} h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. d5 O-O 13. Qd3 $14 {with a small advantage
and an easier-to-play position.} *

