1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 {This line allows us to get
our setup by force. After} d6 $1 {The only move!} (5... Nf6 $2 6. Bf4 $1 e5 7.
Bg5 d6 8. Bxf6 $16 (8. Nd2 $16) 8... gxf6 9. Nd2 $16) 6. c4 {a hedgehog
position arises, where we will discuss the typical plans for White.} Nf6 7.
N5c3 $1 {I like this move compared to the more popular 7.N1c3. White's basic
idea is to develop while preventing the moves ...b5 and ...d5.} Be7 {It does
not matter if Black starts with this or ...a6 etc. - White's will continue in
the same way.} 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O b6 {The best place for Black's light-squared
bishop is on b7.} 10. Bf4 $1 {The move of the famous Canadian Grandmaster
Kevin Spraggett !! IT'S REALLY NOT ABOUT LEARNING BY HEART... IT'S MOSTLY
ABOUT PLANS AND IDEAS AND WHERE TO PUT THE PIECES! WHAT'S THE IDEA BEHIND Bf4?
The idea is to answer to ...d6-d5 by Black, with cxd5! exd5 and e5! - the
bishop is supporting the e5 advance!} ({After} 10. Be3 Bb7 11. Nd2 d5 $1 {
Black equalizes.} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Qxd5 $11) 10... Bb7 (
10... Ne5 11. Nd2 $1) 11. Re1 $1 {This is maybe more accurate than 11.Nd2,
because after 11.Nd2 Black has 11. ..Nd4!?. With Re1 however, I am now ready
to play Nd2 on the next move, and if he goes Nd4 I have Bf1!} (11. Nd2 Nd4 $1
12. Re1 (12. Bd3 Nd7 $132) 12... Nxe2+ 13. Qxe2 $14 {Black is maybe still
better as the absence of this light-squared bishop isn't felt too much. For
instance} Rc8 14. Rac1 a6 15. Nf1 Qc7 16. b3 Rfd8 17. Ng3 Nd7 18. Red1 Qb8 19.
Nh5 $5 {(provoking a weakness)} g6 20. Ng3 $14 {[%cal Yh2h4]}) 11... Rc8 12.
Nd2 {Here are some typical ideas for White now: a3, b4, or Bf1, h3, Qe2(-Qe3!?)
, or Bf1, Bg3, f4, and Qf3! We look at some possible continuations by Black.
The following lines are non-forcing and aim to demonstrate typical setups for
both sides. The play is typical for hedgehog positions: White has more space
and must patiently improve his position before taking concrete actions, while
Black tries to stay flexible and hopes for a counterattack if White is too
hasty.} a6 (12... e5 $2 {A serious positional mistake.} 13. Be3 $16 Nd4 14. Bf1
{Black's active knight doesn't compensate for the weaknesses created by ...e5.
White can play on the queenside with b4 and prepare a4-a5.}) (12... Nd4 13. Bf1
Nd7 14. Be3 Nc6 15. Rc1 $14 {(intending a3 and b4)}) (12... Ne5 13. Rc1 Nfd7 {
After this move Black possibly wants to play ...g5!? As there is no ...d6-d5
anymore I can calmly retreat my Bishop to e3 or to g3!} 14. Bg3 (14. Be3) 14...
g5 {Otherwise White can play f4.} 15. b3 $14 {It makes sense to protect c4 to
be able to play Nf3 (or maybe Nf1).}) (12... d5 $2 {does not work due to} 13.
cxd5 $1 exd5 14. e5 Nd7 15. Bg4 $16) (12... Qc7 13. Rc1 {Now Black already has
to be careful.} Qb8 (13... Rfd8 $2 14. Nd5 $1 exd5 15. cxd5 $16 {White is
better due to the weakness of the d6-pawn.}) (13... Ne5 14. b4 $14 {Due to the
opposition of queen and rook on the c-file this can be played immediately as ..
.d5 doesn't work now.}) 14. Bg3 $14 {followed by further improving the
position.}) 13. Rc1 {White finishes his development. A useful rule: when we
have a choice between several continuations of approximately equal value, it's
good to choose the one that brings new pieces into the game.} Ne5 (13... Qc7 $2
{A typical mistake, and one of the reasons why in hedgehog type of positions,
the knight belongs to d7 and not to c6!} 14. Nd5 $1 exd5 15. cxd5 $16 {White
is better due to the weakness of the d6-pawn.}) 14. a3 $1 (14. b4 $6 {Be
careful NOT to play b4 without a3 first! Because sometimes black has ...d6-d5
ideas attacking b4! SO... FIRST a3! AND THEN b4 !} Ng6 15. Be3 d5 $17 16. cxd5
Bxb4) (14. Bg3 g5 $5) (14. Be3 $1 $14) 14... Qc7 15. b4 $14 {Since a3 and b4
have been already been played, there remain Bf1, h3, Qe2(-Qe3!?), or Bf1, Bg3,
f4, and Qf3! to improve the position.} Qb8 (15... Rfd8 $5 16. Bf1 $14 (16. Bg3
$5 $14) (16. Be3 $5 $14) 16... Qb8 17. h3 Ba8 18. Qe2 h6 19. Qe3 $14) (15...
Nfd7 16. Be3 {Stepping away from a possible ...g5 and preparing f4. In this
case, e3 can be a better square for the bishop - from there it operates on
both flanks.} (16. Bg3 g5 $5) 16... g5 $6 {can be answered by} 17. Nf3 $1 $16 {
to exchange the strong e5-knight.}) 16. Bf1 $14 (16. Be3 $14) (16. h3 $14)
16... Nfd7 17. Be3 $5 (17. Bg3 $5 Rfe8 18. f4 Ng6 19. Qe2 Bf6 (19... Nf6 20. h3
$14) 20. Qe3 $14 {[%cal Yd2f3]}) 17... Rfe8 (17... g5 $6 18. Nf3 $1 $16) 18. f4
Ng6 19. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ye2f2,Yf2b6,Yc3a4,Ya4b6]} *

