{A very beautiful performance by White!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N5c3 Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O b6 10. Bf4 Bb7 11. Re1
Rc8 12. Nd2 Nd4 13. Bf1 e5 $2 {Again this strategical mistake...} 14. Be3 $16
Ne6 15. Rc1 Nd7 16. Qc2 a6 (16... Bg5 {Black could have traded the
dark-squared bishops which is generally in Black's favor.} 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18.
Nf3 Qe7 19. Qd2 $14) 17. Nf3 Nf6 18. Rcd1 Qc7 19. Nd5 $5 {White could also
have prepared Nd5 by, say Qb1, to be able to take back on d5 with the c-pawn.}
Nxd5 20. exd5 Nc5 21. Ng5 {White starts some action on the kingside based on
the fact that the b7-bishop doesn't take part in the game. A risky strategy
that however works perfectly in the game.} g6 22. h4 $5 f6 23. Nf3 f5 24. Bh6
Rf7 25. b4 Ne4 26. Qb3 Kh8 27. Rc1 Bf6 28. Bd3 Qd7 29. Bxe4 fxe4 30. Rxe4 Qf5
31. Rce1 b5 32. c5 dxc5 33. bxc5 Rxc5 34. Nxe5 $1 {White has correctly
calculated that she can give away f2 with check.} Bxe5 35. Rxe5 Qxf2+ 36. Kh2
Rf8 (36... Qxh4+ 37. Qh3 $18 {Re8 is coming.}) 37. Re8 Rc8 38. Rxf8+ Rxf8 39.
Qc3+ 1-0

