{In this wonderful game between two super-strong GMs again we reach the
Spraggett System by a very different move order!} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. a3 Be7 7. e4 O-O 8. Nf3 {Necessary to stop ...d5.
} d6 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bf4 a6 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. b4 (13. Re1 {would have
been best.} Ne5 14. Nd2) 13... Ng4 ({After} 13... a5 {White should defend his
pawn on b4 with} 14. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rb5] when the point of playing ...a5 is
not clear, while the square b5 has been weakened.} (14. b5 $2 {is wrong as
Black's knight can go to the c5-square.} Nb8 $132 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yb8d7,Yd7c5]
})) 14. Nd2 Nge5 15. Be3 $1 {The bishop can move as ...d5 is no longer
possible.} Re8 (15... f5 $2 {just leads to a weakening of Black's position.}
16. exf5 Rxf5 17. f4 Nd7 18. Bg4 $18) (15... g5 $2 16. Na4 $1 Nd7 17. Nf3 $1
$16 {Black can't justify the move ...g5.}) 16. Kh1 {Here and on the next moves
White avoids to commit himself.} (16. f4 {was quite good too.} Nd7 (16... Ng6
$2 17. Na4 $16) 17. Nb3) 16... Bf8 17. f3 $3 {White is in no hurry! First, he
stabilizes the position and later he will take more concrete action!} Nd7 18.
Qe1 $6 (18. Qb3) 18... a5 $1 19. b5 Ncb8 $6 (19... Nce5 $14) 20. Na4 d5 21.
cxd5 $16 {The d6-d5 advance doesn't always lead to a good position for black !!
} Rxc1 $6 (21... exd5 22. Rxc8 Qxc8 23. Qc1 $1 $14) 22. Qxc1 exd5 23. Bg1 $16 {
White is better due to the weakness of b6.} Re6 (23... dxe4 24. Nxe4 Bxe4 25.
fxe4 Rxe4 26. Bd1 $5 $16 {[%csl Gd1,Gg1][%cal Yd1b3] With his strong bishops
White has more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 24. Bd1 dxe4 25. Nxe4
Ne5 26. Bb3 Rg6 27. Rd1 Nbd7 28. Nac3 Qh4 29. Bd5 Bxd5 30. Nxd5 Rh6 31. Rd4 Qh5
32. Nf4 Qh4 33. Nd5 Qh5 34. Qf4 Qg6 35. a4 $1 Qe6 36. Qd2 Qf5 37. Ne3 Qf4 38.
Rxd7 Nxd7 39. Qxd7 Re6 40. Qd1 Qc7 41. Nd5 Qb7 42. Qd4 f5 43. Qc4 Kh8 44. Nf4
Re8 45. Ng5 1-0

