{By a totally different move order, Magnus Carlsen reaches a position from the
Spraggett variation of the Taimanov Sicilian.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. a3 Bc5 ({We can reach our setup also after} 6... Be7
7. e4 O-O 8. Nf3 d6 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bf4 Rc8 12. Rc1 Re8 13. Re1 Ne5
14. Nd2) 7. Nb3 Be7 8. e4 O-O 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bf4 d6 12. Rc1 Rc8 13.
Re1 Ne5 14. Nd2 {Again White has achieved the basic setup of the Spraggett
Variation.} Nfd7 15. Be3 (15. Bg3 g5 $5) 15... Qc7 (15... g5 16. b4 $14) (15...
Nc5 16. Qc2 $14 d5 $6 17. exd5 exd5 18. cxd5 Bxd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20. b4 $16) 16.
b4 Qb8 17. f4 Ng6 18. g3 $16 {In general White has to be careful with moves
like this, as weakening the king's position can also backfire. However Black's
knight on g6 is misplaced and White manages to consolidate his space advantage.
At the time when this game was played, Ian Nepomniachtchi was the second of
Magnus Carlsen (yes indeed!) and he suggested the very opening system played
in this game for White.} Rfe8 19. Bf3 Qa8 20. Bf2 Ngf8 21. Qe2 Qb8 22. Red1 g6
$2 {This turns out to be a serious weakening. It was better to keep waiting
with for instance ...a6 and ...Rc7+/=.} (22... h6 23. Nb3 a6 24. b5 a5 25. Na4
Nc5 (25... d5) 26. Nbxc5 dxc5 27. Qf1 Ba8) 23. e5 $3 $16 {AN amazing move by
the World Champion! Now the e5-pawn appears to be weak, but in fact black has
no way to attack it efficiently and his knight on f8 is extremely passive!} Bc6
(23... dxe5 24. fxe5 Bxf3 25. Nxf3 $16) 24. Bd4 Red8 25. Bxc6 Rxc6 26. Nf3 dxe5
27. fxe5 Rdc8 28. Ne4 Qc7 29. Nfd2 a6 30. Nf2 Bg5 31. Rf1 Bxd2 32. Qxd2 Nxe5
33. Bxe5 Qxe5 34. Ng4 Rd6 35. Nh6+ Kg7 36. Rxf7+ Kh8 37. Qf2 Qd4 38. c5 bxc5
39. Qxd4+ Rxd4 40. Rxc5 Rcd8 41. Rcc7 Rd1+ 42. Kg2 R1d2+ 43. Kh3 R2d5 44. Ng4
Rh5+ 45. Kg2 Rd2+ 46. Kf3 Rf5+ 47. Ke3 Rxf7 48. Rxf7 Rd8 49. Nf6 Rb8 50. Kf4 h6
51. Ke5 a5 52. bxa5 Ra8 53. a6 1-0

