1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 {The Kan Variation is very flexible,
but also allows White a lot of freedom as Black's setup is a little slow.} 5.
Bd3 {The most comfortable move - it requires zero theoretical knowledge! Just
develop the pieces and play c4.} Bc5 (5... Qc7 $5 {The hedgehog set-up - we
have many good ways to develop our pieces. Here is one:} 6. O-O Nf6 (6... b5 $6
7. a4 $1 {Here we see that ...b5 is ineffective without a white knight on c3 -
White can simply play a4.} b4 8. c3 Bb7 9. Qe2 bxc3 10. Nxc3 d6 11. Bg5 $16) 7.
Qe2 $1 {Provoking ...d6 as e5 is now a threat.} d6 (7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5
$16) 8. c4 {After Black has closed the diagonal for the f8-bishop it is a good
moment to play c4.} Nbd7 9. f4 $1 (9. Nc3 $5 Ne5 {White can afford to exchange
his bishop for the knight as Black falls behind in development.} 10. h3 Be7 11.
Be3 O-O 12. Rac1 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 $14 {White has a nice position, e.g.} b6 14. f4
Bb7 15. f5 $1 e5 $6 16. Nd5 $16) 9... b6 (9... g6 10. f5) 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. f5 $1
e5 12. Nb3 Be7 13. Be3 $16) (5... Nf6 6. O-O d6 (6... Nc6 $2 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5
Nd5 9. c4 Ne7 10. Nc3 $16) (6... Qc7 {leads to 5...Qc7.}) 7. c4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O
9. b3 {--> see model game Sasikiran-Spraggett.} (9. Be3 $5)) (5... Qb6 6. Nb3 {
followed by c4.}) (5... Nc6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. O-O d5 8. c4 $1 $16 {--> see model
game Domogaev-Arakeljan.}) (5... g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Be3 $14 {--> see model game
Mastrovasilis-Gajek.}) 6. Nb3 Be7 $6 {In my opinion, this system is bad for
Black.} (6... Ba7 $5 {The most simple plan is to exchange the a7-bishop with
c4-Qe2-Be3!, with nice pressure!} 7. O-O Ne7 (7... Nf6 $2 8. e5 $16) 8. Qe2
Nbc6 9. c4 O-O 10. Be3 d6 11. Nc3 (11. Bxa7 $5 Rxa7 12. Nc3 e5 13. Qe3 Be6 14.
Rfd1 $14) 11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3 e5 13. Rfd1 Be6 14. Be2 $14) 7. Qg4 $1 (7. O-O $5
d6 (7... Nf6 $2 8. e5 $16) 8. Qg4 $5 {transposes} g6 9. Qe2) 7... g6 (7... Nf6
$2 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qh6 Rxg2 10. Qh3 $1 (10. e5 $5 $16 Qb6 11. Be3 Ng4 12. Bxb6
Nxh6 13. N1d2 $16) 10... Rg8 11. e5 Nd5 12. Qxh7 $18) 8. Qe2 $1 {After having
provoked ...g6 we come back to e2 so as not to run into ...Nf6.} d6 9. O-O Nd7
{And now we look at two plans: a4 followed by Na3, or c4 followed by Nc3.} (
9... Nf6 10. Bh6 $1 $16) 10. a4 $1 (10. c4 $1 Ngf6 11. Nc3 O-O (11... h5 12.
Bg5 $16) 12. Bh6 Re8 13. f4 $16) 10... b6 11. Na3 $1 Bb7 (11... Ngf6 12. Bh6
Bb7 13. a5 b5 14. Nxb5 $3 (14. c4 $16) 14... axb5 15. Bxb5 $16) 12. Nc4 ({or} 
12. a5 $5 b5 13. Nxb5 $5 axb5 14. Bxb5 $16) 12... Qc7 13. Be3 Ngf6 14. a5 b5
15. Nb6 $16 *

