1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. a3 $1 {A very
interesting way to get out of book early! Now, we can try plans with short or
long castling! BE CAREFULL !! ... after 6.a3! black should avoid 3 bad (or
very bad ) moves! 6...a6? , 6...Bc5? and 6... d5?! CHECK THE NOTES!} ({There
is a lot of theory after} 6. Ndb5) ({and} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4) 6...
Be7 $1 {Pretty much THE ONLY good move for black !} (6... Bc5 $2 {Possibly the
worst move !!} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Ne4 {Due to 6...Bc5? our knight is
coming to e4 with tempo!} Be7 10. c4 $18 {White is already positionally
winning, e.g.} f5 11. cxd5 fxe4 12. d6) (6... a6 $2 {The second worst move!} 7.
Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Ne4 {This is the main line...BUT WITH THE MOVES a3 and
a6 INCLUDED!! This clearly helps White because Black does have neither the ...
Ba6 nor the ...Bb4+ ideas!!} Qc7 10. Qh5 $1 $16 ({or} 10. f4 $16 f5 11. exf6
gxf6 12. Qh5+ $16) 10... g6 (10... Be7 11. c4 Nb6 12. Bf4 $18) 11. Qg5 Be7 12.
Qg3 f6 13. Nd6+ $18) (6... d5 $6 {The best of the "bad" moves. It leads to
positions with an isolated d-pawn and a small advantage for White.} 7. Bb5 $1
Bd7 8. exd5 exd5 (8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. O-O Be7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Bd3 $5 $14
{The threat to win a pawn by Qh5 provokes a further concession.}) 9. O-O Be7
10. Be2 $1 (10. Nde2 $5) 10... O-O 11. Bf3 $14) (6... d6 {Now we have many
good ideas! Just pick one! But the best by far is 8.Qe2!!} 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qe2 $3
{PROBABLY THE BEST MOVE AND a very interesting idea. We want to castle long
and attack! We will play either g4! (if it is not a blunder due to some ...
e6-e5 ideas) or f4! with a strong attack, while our a3 move is very relevant
and useful!} O-O (8... a6 9. O-O-O Qc7 10. g4 $1 {Whenever this move does not
blunder the g4-pawn it is very strong.} Nxd4 11. Rxd4 $1 b5 (11... e5 12. Rc4
Qb8 13. g5 $18) 12. g5 Nd7 13. f4 $3 {note this very usefull a3 move!!!} Bb7 (
13... Nb6 14. Qf2 $3 {ALWAYS Qf2 when I see ...Nb6! to take control of the
c4-square.}) 14. Rg1 $16 Nb6 15. Qf2 $3 O-O 16. f5 $18) (8... Nxd4 $5 9. Bxd4
e5 10. Be3 Be6 11. O-O-O O-O 12. f3 $1 Rc8 (12... Qa5 13. Qe1 $5 {[%cal Yc3d5,
Yg2g4,Yg4g5] Preventing ...d5 and threatening Nd5. White is also better after
other queen moves.} (13. Qb5 $5 Qc7 14. g4) (13. Qd2) ({But not} 13. g4 $2 d5
$1 $132) 13... Rfc8 14. g4 $16) 13. Qd2 {Defending against ...Rxc3.} a6 (13...
b5 14. g4 $1 $16) (13... Qa5 14. g4 $16 Rxc3 $2 15. Qxc3 $18) 14. g4 $16) (8...
e5 9. Nb3 $14 {In this Najdorf type of position, our a3 move may not be so
relevant, but Black has played ...e5 in 2 moves, and of course his knight
should be on d7 and not on c6!!} Be6 10. O-O-O a6 11. Nd5 $16 (11. f3 $16)) (
8... d5 $6 9. O-O-O O-O 10. g4 $1 $16 Bd7 (10... Qc7 11. exd5 (11. Ndb5 $16)
11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bg2 $16) 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bg2 $16)
9. O-O-O {and, as said above, our next move (if possible) will be g4...if not,
it will be f4!} Qc7 (9... e5 10. Nb3 a6 11. Qe1 $3 (11. f3 b5 $36) 11... b5 12.
Nd5 $14) (9... Bd7 $5 10. f4 $1 $36 (10. f3 $36) (10. g4 $6 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 e5
12. Be3 Bxg4) 10... Rc8 $2 11. g4 $36 Nxd4 (11... e5 $2 12. Nf5 $18) 12. Bxd4
e5 13. fxe5 $3 Bxg4 14. exf6 Bxe2 15. fxe7 Qxe7 16. Bxe2 $18) 10. g4 $3 $36
Nxd4 (10... Bd7 $2 11. g5 {After a g5 move in the Najdorf-Schevenigen set-ups,
Black must always be ready to play ...Nd7! (or ...Nh5). If he is forced to
play ...Ne8 then he is almost always lost!} Ne8 12. f4 $18 (12. h4 $18)) 11.
Rxd4 $1 e5 (11... a6 12. g5 Nd7 13. f4 b5 14. h4 $16 (14. Rg1 $16) 14... Nb6
15. Qf2 $1 $16) 12. Rc4 $1 Qb8 13. g5 Ne8 14. Nd5 $16) (6... Qc7 $6 {This is a
bad Taimanov for Black, because after 7.Be3-a6 Back would like to take back
the move ...Nf6 and play b5! instead!!} 7. Be3 a6 8. f4 $1 d6 (8... d5 9. e5
Nd7 {We have reached a favorable version of the French Defence. Now White has
a few promising options.} 10. h4 $5 (10. Qg4 $5 h5 11. Qg3 $14) (10. Qd2 $14)
10... Bc5 11. Qd2 $14 {/+/-}) 9. Qf3 Be7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Nxc6 $1 (11. g4 Nxd4
12. Rxd4 e5 $13 {[%csl Rd4,Rg4]}) 11... bxc6 12. g4 d5 13. g5 Nxe4 (13... Nd7
14. h4 Rb8 15. h5 $16) 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qxe4 c5 16. Qe5 $5 $16) 7. Nxc6 $1 {
ALSO VERY INTERESTING AND ALSO WITHOUT THEORY! Perhaps this is the most simple
idea and we should prefer it!} (7. Be3 $5 {Now we are hoping for 7...d6?! 8.
Qe2!!, transposing to a favorable variation!} O-O (7... d6 8. Qe2 $3 {see 6...
d6 7.Qe2!}) 8. Bd3 (8. Qe2 $6 {Unfortunately, this does not work here, because
Black has d5!!} d5 $1 $36) (8. Be2 $5 d6 (8... d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5
11. O-O $14) 9. O-O $5 (9. Qd3 $5 Bd7 10. f4) 9... a6 10. f4 Qc7 11. Kh1 Bd7
12. Qe1 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bc6 14. Qg3)) 7... bxc6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Qg4 $1 g6 (9... Kf8
10. Qg3 $14 d6 11. exd6 Bxd6 12. Qd3) 10. Qg3 $1 $14 *

