1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Bd3 Nc6 $1 {Without exaggeration,
this is maybe the ONLY good move after 5. Bd3.} 6. Nxc6 $1 {This is THE
SIMPLEST and a very interesting concept.!!..we just take on c6 .. and (IF
BLACK PLAYS e6 WE PLAY c4 ), but if black plays with g6-Bg7, then we should
probably avoid c4!} (6. Be3 $1 {This is another good move! Now ...g6 and ...
Ng4 are playable!} Ng4 (6... g6 $5 7. h3 $5 Bg7 8. c4 {Now Black has to be
careful to not fall into a passive position, typical for the Maroczy bind!} O-O
(8... Qa5+ $2 9. Nc3 Ng4 10. hxg4 Bxd4 (10... Nxd4 $2 11. O-O $16 O-O 12. f4
$16 (12. Rc1 $16) 12... e5 13. f5)) (8... Ng4 $5 {Black's best line, leading
to an equal position if he knows what to do!} 9. hxg4 Bxd4 $1 10. Bxd4 Nxd4 11.
Nc3 e5 12. f3 $132) (8... Bd7 9. Nc3 Rc8 10. Qd2 $16 Ne5 11. b3 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3
O-O 13. O-O a6 14. a4 $16) 9. Nc3 Bd7 10. Nf3 $3 $14 (10. Be2 $14) (10. Nde2
$14) 10... Nb4 (10... Rc8 11. Rc1 Be6 (11... Nb4 12. O-O $16 (12. Be2 $16 Bc6
13. a3 Na6 14. Nd2 Nc5 15. Qc2 $1 $16)) 12. b3 $16 {White has stabilized and
will play 0-0 on the next move, with a nice advantage.}) 11. O-O Nxd3 12. Qxd3
$16) (6... e5 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. O-O Be7 (8... Ng4 9. Bc1 $5 $14 (9. Bd2 {see
model game Elia Reyes-Sandoval.}) 9... Be7 (9... Qh4 10. h3 Nf6 11. Nd2 $16)
10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3 Be6 12. b3 Nf6 13. h3 Nd7 (13... Qc7 14. Be3 $14) 14. Be2 $1
) 9. c4 {This positions are slightly better for White as Black struggles to
find an active plan.} O-O 10. Nc3 Be6 (10... Nd7 11. Be2 $1 {White avoids ...
Bg5 (as d6 would hang) and prepares to play Bg4 in some positions.} Nc5 {
can be answered by} (11... Rb8 12. b3) 12. b4 Ne6 13. b5 $14) (10... Ne8 11. c5
$5 {An important positional idea in these structures!} dxc5 (11... d5 $2 12.
exd5 cxd5 13. Nxd5 $18) 12. Na4 $14) 11. Qe2 (11. b3 $5 d5 $140 12. exd5 cxd5
13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 (14... Bxd5 15. Qe2 e4 16. Bc4 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 $16)
15. Qe2 $14) (11. h3 $5) 11... Nd7 12. Rfd1 $14) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 (7... Nxe3 $2 {
doesn't equalize in the end:} 8. Nxd8 Nxd1 9. Nxf7 $1 Nxf2 (9... Kxf7 10. Kxd1
$16) 10. Nxh8 Nxh1 11. Nc3 g6 12. Nd5 $1 Rb8 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7 15. c3
$5 Bg7 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Ke2 $16 {and after picking up the h1-knight White
stays a pawn up.}) 8. Bd2 $5 (8. Bd4 $5 e5 9. Bc3 Be7 10. h3 Nf6 11. O-O O-O
12. Nd2 Be6 13. Re1 Qc7 14. Bc4 $14) 8... Qb6 (8... e5 9. h3 Nf6 10. c4 Be7 11.
O-O O-O 12. Nc3 $14 {with the typical advantage !} Be6 13. Qe2 $14 (13. b3 $14
d5 14. exd5 cxd5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Qe2 $16 Nxc3 17. Bxc3 f6 18. Rfd1 Qb6 19. b4
$16 (19. Bc4))) 9. O-O Qxb2 10. Bc3 $3 Qb6 11. Nd2 $36 e5 (11... Qc5 $5 12. Bb2
Rb8 13. Nb3 Qb6 14. Bc3 $14 {with very good attacking chances} (14. Rb1 $14))
12. Nc4 Qc7 13. Ba5 $16) 6... bxc6 7. O-O (7. c4 g6 $1 $132 (7... e6 $6 8. Nc3
$14) (7... e5 $6 8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 $14 (10. h3 $14))) 7... g6 $1 {
After this correct move, we reach positions that are about equal, but where we
have the easier play! Please note that it is rarely a good idea for White to
play c4 here (when Black plays ...g6 after we took Nxc6), and it is seldom a
good idea for Black to exchange the dark-squared bishops !!} (7... e5 $6 8. c4
Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 $5 (10. b3 Nd7 11. Be2 (11. b4 $5 $14) 11... Nc5 12. Be3
Ne6 13. Qd2 $14) 10... Be6 11. Qe2 a5 12. Rfd1 $14 (12. Rad1) 12... Qc7 (12...
Ng4 13. Bd2) 13. h3 Rfd8 14. b3 Qb7 15. Rac1 $16 {With a very passive position
for Black !!}) (7... e6 $6 8. c4 Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bf4 $3 $14 {provoking e5 !!
} (10. Be3 $14) 10... e5 (10... Qc7 11. Rc1 a5 12. Qe2 $14) 11. Be3 $14 Ng4 12.
Bd2 $14) 8. b3 $1 (8. c4 $6 {No, this doesn't fit here !! This is good only
when black has played e6 or e5.} Bg7 9. Nc3 Nd7 10. Be3 O-O $132) 8... Bg7 9.
Bb2 {White's b2-bishop will eliminate the strong bishop on g7.} O-O 10. Nc3 $5
(10. Nd2 $5 Nd7 $6 (10... Re8 $132) (10... a5 11. a4 Qc7 12. Re1 Nd7 $6 13.
Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qf3 Ne5 15. Qg3 $14) 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Nc4 Nc5 13. b4 (13. Re1
$14) 13... Nxd3 14. cxd3 $14) 10... Nd7 $6 (10... d5 $5 11. Re1 dxe4 12. Bxe4
$1 $14 Nxe4 13. Rxe4 Qc7 14. Na4 e5 15. Qe2 Re8 16. Re1 f6 (16... f5 17. Bxe5 (
17. Rxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe5)) 17. Nc5 Bf5 18. Qc4+ Qf7 19. Qxf7+ Kxf7 20. Rc4 Bf8
21. g4 Bxg4 22. Rxg4 Bxc5 23. Rc4 Be7 24. Rxc6 Rec8 25. Rxc8 Rxc8 26. Re2 g5
27. h3 h5 28. c4 Ke6 29. Bd4 a6 30. Kg2 g4 31. hxg4 hxg4 32. Bc3 Rd8 {1/2-1/2
Grandelius,N-Gledura,B/Budva MNE 2023}) (10... Qc7 11. Re1 Nd7 12. Na4 $1 e5
13. Bf1 $14 (13. c4 $5 $14 {an exception... c4 is good here ! ...with the
bisgop on g7 blocked !!})) (10... Re8 11. Re1 $14 (11. Na4 $5) (11. Qd2 $5))
11. Na4 $1 {We want to trade the dark-square bishops here.} Bxb2 12. Nxb2 $14
Nc5 (12... d5 $6 13. Re1 $14 (13. Qd2 $14 e5 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Rfe1 Re8 16. Na4
$14) 13... Nc5 14. Qc1 $5) 13. Qd2 Nxd3 (13... Rb8 $6 14. Rae1 $14 (14. Rfe1
$14 e5 $2 15. Bc4 $16 Qc7 16. Rad1 Rd8 17. Qe3 $16)) 14. Nxd3 (14. cxd3) 14...
c5 15. Rfe1 *

