1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {A playable line without much theory! The basic
plan is to play a fast 0-0, followed by Re1, and then c3-d4! Possibly after
moving Bf1 or Bb5 first!} e6 $1 {This is the best!} (3... Nf6 {This is not so
good in my view and yet it is quite popular.} 4. e5 Ng4 {And now, first of all,
WE DO NOT GET TOO EXCITED! The position is playable for Black! And secondly,
we don't need much theory again just develop fast, keep the queens on the
board of course, and try to attack long-term!} (4... d5 5. Bb5 $1 Nd7 6. Bxc6
$1 {Now we are ready to follow the typical strategies against the doubled
c-pawns!} bxc6 7. d3 e6 (7... g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 $14 {--> model game
Souleidis-Zhigalko.}) (7... Nb6 8. h3 $1 {(not allowing ...Bg4)} (8. Nbd2 $1
$14 Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 e6 11. O-O $14) 8... c4 9. d4 (9. O-O cxd3 10. cxd3
$14 {[%csl Rc6]}) 9... e6 10. O-O c5 11. Be3 $1 $14 Nd7 12. Nc3 Rb8 13. b3 $16)
8. O-O Be7 (8... Rb8 {--> see model game Beerdsen-Zhigalko.}) 9. Qe2 $14 {
Black has a horrible bishop on c8 so he tries to attack our king in order not
to end up completely passive!} g5 (9... O-O 10. c4 $14) 10. c4 h5 11. Nc3 Ba6
12. Re1 g4 13. Nd2 $14) 5. Qe2 $1 {This is objectively better than the
immediate 5.Bxf7 and leads to a small advantage for White.} (5. Bxf7+ $5 Kxf7
6. Ng5+ Kg8 (6... Ke8 7. Qxg4 Nxe5 8. Qg3 $14 {We are not winning or anything,
but don't forget that black has lost his castling rights! So we have a
long-term chance of an attack!} (8. Qe4 d6 9. d3 (9. f4 Nc6 10. Nxh7 $14) 9...
g6 10. Bf4 Bf5 11. Qd5 $14) 8... d6 (8... Nc6 9. Nxh7) 9. O-O (9. Na3 $5 $14)
9... g6 10. d3 Bg7 11. Nc3 $16) 7. Qxg4 Nxe5 8. Qe4 $1 Nc6 (8... Qc7 9. f4 $1
Nc6 (9... Nf7 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Nc3 e6 12. O-O d5 13. Qf3 $16 Bd6 14. f5) 10.
Qf5 $1 Nd8 11. O-O g6 12. Qe4 $14 Qc6 13. Qe2 d6 14. d3 h6 15. Nf3 $16) (8...
d6 $2 9. Qd5+ e6 10. Nxe6 $16) 9. Qf5 $5 Qe8 10. Qxc5 b6 11. Qe3 d5 $44 {
We have won a pawn, but Black has good compensation for it.}) 5... Qc7 6. Bxf7+
Kxf7 7. Qc4+ Ke8 8. Qxg4 g6 (8... Nxe5 $6 9. Qh5+ Nf7 10. O-O g6 11. Qh4) 9.
O-O {Good enough, though the alternatives are also interensting.} (9. Qg3) (9.
d4 $5) 9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Nc3 $14) (3... a6 4. d4 $1 {Is some kind of
open Sicilian, but we will make sure to get out of book pretty fast!} cxd4 (
4... b5 5. d5 $1 $16) 5. Nxd4 Qc7 (5... e6 6. O-O Qc7 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Qe2 $14)
6. Nxc6 $5 {Totally out of book...for both players!} dxc6 (6... bxc6 7. Qe2 $14
) (6... Qxc6 7. Qe2 $14) 7. Qe2 $14) (3... d6 4. O-O g6 {This setup is just
too slow.} 5. c3 Bg7 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 Nf6 8. d5 $1 $16 {White gets a big
advantage after this, e.g.} Ne5 (8... Nb8 9. Nc3 O-O 10. h3 {Preventing ...Bg4
and preparing Be3.} a6 11. a4 Nbd7 12. Be3) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Qb3 a6
12. a4 Ne8 13. Be3 Nd6 14. Be2 f5 15. f3 f4 16. Bb6) (3... g6 {transposes to 2.
..g6.}) 4. O-O {Now, if Black plays passive moves, we follow our main plan:
Re1! followed by c3 and d4 (possibly with the inclusion of Bf1, Bb5, or even
Bb3).} d5 $1 {This is a playable and good move. Now we can choose between the
fashionable 5.Bb5 and the more simple (and in my view better) 5.exd5 !} (4...
Nf6 $1 5. Re1 Nxe4 $5 {This is interesting and playable !!} (5... d6 $6 {
SUPER SOS !!! THIS KIND OF SLOW PLAY IS WHAT YOU WILL GET VERY OFTEN...SO,
PLAY Re1 !, MOVE THE Bc4 somewhere, and play c3-d4 !} 6. Bf1 $1 (6. c3 $2 {
CAREFUL!!} Nxe4 $3 $17) (6. Bb3 $1 Be7 7. c3 O-O 8. d4 $14 {Some sample lines
now !} cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nbd2 (11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bd7 13. Qd3
Rc8 14. Bc2 g6 15. Bh6 Re8 16. h4 (16. Qe3) 16... Bxh4 17. g3 Be7 18. Kg2 Qc7
19. Rac1) 11... f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Nf1 Bd7 14. Ng3) (6. Bb5 $1 Bd7 (6... Be7
7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. e5) 7. c3 a6 8. Bf1 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 d5 (10... O-O 11.
d5 $16) 11. e5 Ne4 12. Nbd2 Nxd2 (12... f5 13. exf6) (12... Bb4 $2 13. Nxe4 $1
dxe4 14. Rxe4 $18) 13. Bxd2 O-O 14. Bd3 Rc8 15. Rc1 $16) 6... Be7 7. c3 O-O (
7... e5 8. h3 O-O 9. d4 $14) 8. d4 $14 cxd4 (8... Bd7 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. e5 Nd5
11. Bd3 (11. Nbd2) 11... Qc7 12. Qc2 g6 (12... h6 13. Qe2) 13. Bh6 Rfd8 14.
Nbd2) (8... Qc7 9. d5 $16) 9. cxd4 d5 (9... e5 10. d5 Nb8 11. h3 Nbd7 12. Nc3
a6 13. a4 $16 {[%cal Yc1e3]}) (9... b6 10. Nc3 $16) 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nc3 $1 $16 (
11. Bd3 $5 f5 $1 12. exf6 Bxf6 $1 (12... Nxf6 $2 13. Nc3 Bd7 14. Ng5 $16 (14.
Bb5) (14. Bg5)) 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Rxe4 b5 $132) (11. Nbd2 $1 $14)) (5... d5 $6
6. exd5 Nxd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 $14) 6. Rxe4 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qd8 (8...
Qd7 $5 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Be7 (10... b6 $6 11. Bf4 $14 Bb7 $4 12. Ndb5 $1 $18)
11. Nxc6 $3 Qxd1+ (11... Qxc6 12. Rg4 $3 g6 13. Qe2 $1 (13. Bh6 $36) 13... O-O
14. Rc4 Qa6 15. Bh6 Rd8 16. Re1 $36) 12. Nxd1 bxc6 13. Rc4 Bd7 14. Be3 $1 $14 {
we have a nice advantage here..we will stabilize..and possible go for Bc5}) (
8... Qf5 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Rxd4 Be7 12. Be3 O-O 13. Qe2 {The
position is equal but playable!} Bf6 $6 14. Rf4 $1 Qg6 $6 15. Rg4 $1 Qf5 16.
Ne4 $16 {1/2 (42)-1/2 Adhiban,B-Sethuraman,S/chess24.com INT 2022/CBM 207 Extra
}) 9. d4 Be7 (9... cxd4 $6 10. Nxd4 Be7 (10... Bd7 $6 11. Qg4 $1 $16 (11. Ndb5
$5 $14)) 11. Qg4 $1 O-O 12. Bh6 Bf6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qg3 Kh8 15. Bf4 $16) 10.
Bf4 $1 cxd4 (10... g5 $2 11. d5 $3 $16 gxf4 (11... exd5 12. Nxd5 gxf4 13. Rxe7+
$3 $18 Kf8 (13... Nxe7 14. Nf6+ Kf8 15. Qxd8+ $18) 14. Re4 $1 $18 Be6 15. c4)
12. dxc6 $16) 11. Nxd4 O-O 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qf3 $14 {We ave good attacking
possibilities!}) (4... a6 $6 5. Re1 b5 6. Bf1 Nge7 7. a4 $1 (7. c3 $14) 7... b4
8. c3 d5 9. d3 $3 $16 dxe4 10. dxe4) (4... Nge7 $6 5. Re1 (5. d4 $5) 5... Ng6
6. c3 $1 $14 (6. d4 $5 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Be7 8. Bf1 O-O 9. c4) 6... Be7 7. d4 d5 8.
exd5 exd5 9. Bb3 $14) 5. exd5 $1 (5. Bb5 $5 {Black's best chance is to accept
the gambit!} dxe4 $1 (5... a6 $6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d3 $16) (5... Bd7 $6 6. exd5
exd5 7. d4 $1 $16 {Black is seriously behind in his development and once again,
we do not need to know any theory - just logical attacking moves!} (7. Re1+ $5
Be7 8. d3 Nf6 9. Qe2)) (5... Be7 $5 6. d3 $5 (6. Nc3 $5 Nf6 7. exd5 exd5 8. d4
$14) 6... Nf6 7. e5 Nd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. c4 $14) (5... Bd6 $6 6. Re1 $5 $14) 6.
Ne5 Nge7 $1 (6... Bd7 $2 7. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Nc3 Nf6 (9... f5 10.
Qe2 $1 Nf6 $140 11. d3 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge2,Re6][%cal Ye2e6]}) 10. Qe2 Qd4 11. Re1
Be7 12. Nxe4 $14) (6... Qd5 $2 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Nc3 Qd7 9. Ba4 Nf6 10. Qe2 $16)
(6... Qc7 $1 7. Nxc6 bxc6 (7... a6 $5 {what a move !!} 8. Nd4+ $1 Kd8 9. Be2
cxd4 10. d3 $44) 8. Bc4 Bd6 9. h3 Nf6 $6 10. Nc3 Bh2+ 11. Kh1 Be5 12. Re1 $14)
7. Nxc6 Nxc6 (7... bxc6 8. Ba4 $44) 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Re1 Bd6 10. Nc3 f5 11. d3
exd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Rd1 Bc7 14. Qc4 $14) 5... exd5 6. Bb3 $1 Nf6 (6... Bd6 $2
7. Bxd5 $3 Bxh2+ 8. Nxh2 Qxd5 9. Nc3 Qd8 10. Ne4 b6 11. d4 $3 $16 cxd4 12. Bf4
$16 {we caught him undeveloped !}) (6... Be7 7. d4 $1 c4 8. Ba4 Bd7 $2 9. Re1
Nf6 10. Qe2 $16) (6... Be6 7. d4 c4 8. Ba4 $14) 7. d4 $1 c4 (7... Be7 8. dxc5
Bxc5 9. Nc3 Be6 10. Bg5 $16 O-O 11. Qd3 $1 Be7 12. Rad1) 8. Ba4 Bd6 (8... Be7
9. Ne5 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. Bg5 O-O 12. c3 Rfe8 13. Nd2 $14) 9. Re1+ Be6 10.
Bg5 $3 O-O 11. Nbd2 $14 {with a very plesant and risk-free advantage..we wll
continue with c3 and maybe b3..or maybe just take on c6 !} a6 12. c3 $1 (12.
Bxc6 $5 bxc6 13. c3 h6 14. Bh4 Be7 15. Ne5 Qc7 16. b3) 12... b5 13. Bc2 $16 Bg4
14. Nf1 h6 15. Bh4 Bh5 16. Ne3 $16 Be7 17. h3 *

