{This is a nice example of how to play against slow play by Black!} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 d6 {Black does not start with 2...Nc6, but the game will later transpose
to our repertoire.} 3. Bc4 e6 4. O-O Nf6 5. Re1 Be7 (5... Nc6 6. Bf1 (6. c3 $2
Nxe4 $1 $15) (6. Bb5 $5) 6... Be7 7. c3 O-O 8. d4) 6. Bf1 {[%cal Yc2c3,Yd2d4]}
O-O 7. c3 Nc6 (7... d5 $2 8. e5 Nfd7 9. d4 $16 {We have transposed to a
favorable version of the French Defence. Black's knight is misplaced on d7 -
in the French Advance Variation it is placed on e7 from where it can go to f5!}
) 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 (9... b6 10. Nc3 d5 11. e5 {Again this French type of
position is favorable for White.} Nd7 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. h4 $5 (13. a3 Rc8 14. Qc2
g6 (14... h6 15. Qe2 {Trying to reverse the queen and bishop battery, when
Black would have difficulties defending.}) 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Bb5 $5 {An
instructive positional idea: After having provoked ...g6, White exchanges his
light-squared bishop. Black will be left with passive pieces only!} a6 17. Bxc6
Rxc6 18. Qd2 b5 19. Qf4 Nb6 20. Nd1 $18 {[%cal Yd1e3,Ye3g4]}) 13... Bxh4 $140
14. Nxh4 Qxh4 15. Re3 $1 {[%cal Ye3h3] with a tremendous attack.}) 10. e5 Ne4 {
We will often come across such a position and it is important to know what to
do. There are three ways to treat this position:} 11. Nc3 {It is best to
exchange Black's strong knight with this or Nbd2.} ({White can try to win a
pawn by} 11. Bd3 f5 (11... Nb4 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Rxe4 Bd7 14. Rg4 Kh8 15. Nc3
$16 {Black does not have enough compensation. White is a pawn up and his
pieces are very active.}) 12. exf6 Bxf6 $1 (12... Nxf6 $2 13. Nc3 $16 {Here
White is clearly better due to Black's weaknesses.}) 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Rxe4 b5
$1 {Here Black has some compensation!}) (11. Nbd2 {was played in the game and
also led to a nice advantage for White.} f5 (11... Nxd2 12. Bxd2 Bd7 (12... Qb6
13. Bc3) 13. Bd3 $16 Re8 14. Qc2 $5 (14. Bb1 $6 Rc8 15. Qc2 g6) 14... g6 (14...
h6 15. Bc3 Rc8 16. Qd2) 15. Bh6 Nb4 16. Qd2 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Rc8 18. Qe3 Bb5 19.
Qf4 $16) 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Nb3 Bd6 14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Bd3 Bf4 16. Bxf4 Qxf4 17.
Qc1 Qd6 18. Qc5 Qd8 19. a3 Nh5 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21. Rxe5 Nf4 22. Qc2 g6 23. Rae1
Qf6 24. Bf1 Bd7 25. g3 Nh5 26. Nc5 Rac8 27. Qd2 Rxc5 28. dxc5 Ng7 29. b4 a6 30.
Bg2 Bc6 31. R1e2 Rd8 32. Qg5 Qxg5 33. Rxg5 d4 34. Bxc6 bxc6 35. Rge5 Kf7 36. g4
h6 37. Rd2 Rd5 38. Rxd5 exd5 39. Rxd4 Ne6 40. Rd2 g5 41. Kg2 Kf6 42. Kf3 Nf4
43. h4 Ke5 44. hxg5 hxg5 45. Rd1 d4 46. Rh1 Kd5 47. Rh7 Kc4 48. Ra7 Kc3 49.
Rxa6 d3 50. Rxc6 d2 51. Rd6 Kc2 52. c6 d1=Q+ 53. Rxd1 Kxd1 54. c7) 11... Nxc3 (
11... f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Ng5 $16 (13. Bg5) (13. Bb5)) 12. bxc3 Bd7 13. Bd3
$16 {White has a backward pawn on c3 but it is easily protected while the
strong center and strong pawn on e5 offer White excellent attacking chances.
For instance} Rc8 14. Qc2 $5 (14. h4 $5 Bxh4 $2 15. Nxh4 Qxh4 16. Ba3 Rfe8 17.
Re3 $18) 14... g6 (14... h6 15. Qd1 $5 {[%cal Yd3b1,Yd1d3]}) (14... Nb4 15.
Bxh7+ Kh8 16. Qb3 Kxh7 17. cxb4) 15. Qd2 1-0

