1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bc4 {We do not play Bc4 against ...e6, but the game
transposes on the next move to our line.} Nc6 4. O-O d6 5. Re1 Nf6 6. Bf1 ({or
} 6. Bb5 Bd7 {Black should protect c6 as White threatened to spoil his pawn
structure.} (6... Be7 $6 7. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 8. e5 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6]}) 7. c3
a6 8. Bf1 {Black may claim to have won a tempo, but ...a6 does not bring him
anything.} Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 {White has built a strong pawn center and
is better.} d5 (10... O-O 11. Nc3 d5 (11... e5 12. d5 Na7 13. h3 $16 {[%csl
Gd5,Ge4] White will start playing on the queenside.}) 12. e5 Ne8 13. Bd3) 11.
e5 Ne4 12. Nbd2 (12. Nc3 $5) 12... Nxd2 (12... f5 13. exf6 $16) (12... Bb4 $2
13. Nxe4 dxe4 (13... Bxe1 14. Nd6+ $18) 14. Rxe4 $18) 13. Bxd2 O-O 14. Bd3 Rc8
15. Rc1 $16) 6... Be7 7. c3 O-O 8. d4 Qc7 $6 (8... Bd7 $6 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. e5
$16 {For instance} Nd5 11. Bd3 (11. Nbd2) 11... Qc7 12. Qc2 g6 (12... h6 13.
Qe2) 13. Bh6 Rfd8 14. Nbd2) 9. dxc5 (9. e5 $16) (9. d5 $16) 9... dxc5 10. e5 {
White is much better due to his space advantage.} Rd8 $2 (10... Nd7 11. Bf4 b6
12. Nbd2 Bb7 13. Bd3 Rad8 14. Qe2 $16) (10... Nd5 11. Bd3 $16) 11. Qc2 (11.
exf6 $1 {would have led to a decisive material advantage.} Rxd1 12. fxe7 Qxe7
13. Rxd1 $18) 11... Nd7 12. Bf4 Nf8 13. h4 $5 (13. Nbd2 Ng6 14. Bg3 {[%cal
Yh2h4]}) 13... Rb8 14. a4 a6 15. Na3 Na5 16. Rad1 Bd7 17. c4 Be8 18. h5 h6 19.
b3 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rd8 21. Bd2 Nc6 22. Bc3 Rxd1 23. Qxd1 Nd7 24. Qa1 Qb6 25. Qb2
Nb4 26. Nc2 Nxc2 27. Qxc2 Nb8 28. Bd3 Bc6 29. Nd2 Qd8 30. Ne4 b6 31. Qe2 Nd7
32. Bc2 Nf8 33. f4 Bxe4 34. Qxe4 f5 35. Qe2 g5 36. hxg6 Qe8 37. Qf3 Qxg6 38.
Bd1 a5 39. Qh3 Qg7 40. Kf2 Ng6 41. g3 Bf8 42. Ke3 Qd7 43. Bc2 Qf7 44. Qh1 Qc7
45. Bd1 Ne7 46. Bf3 Qd7 47. Qg2 Bg7 48. Qh1 Bf8 49. Ba8 Qc8 50. Kd2 Qd7+ 51.
Kc2 Qc8 52. Qg2 Bg7 53. Bf3 Qf8 54. Bh5 Qd8 55. Qb7 Bf8 56. Qg2 Bg7 57. Bf3 Qd7
58. g4 fxg4 59. Bxg4 Nf5 60. Bxf5 exf5 61. Qd5+ Qxd5 62. cxd5 Kf8 63. Be1 Ke7
64. Kc3 h5 65. Bh4+ Kd7 66. Bg5 Bf8 67. d6 Kc6 68. Kd3 Kd7 69. Ke3 Kc6 70. Kf3
