{In this lecture, I provide a full repertoire for White against the Caro-Kann
Defence. My suggestion is based on the Exchange Variation. The starting
position of our repertoire arises after} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3
{This line is very practical since you can play it almost without concrete
theoretical knowledge. What matters, however, is knowing all the subtleties
related to the Carlsbad Structure (with colours reversed in this case). While
the theoretical files will point out the most promising variations, make sure
to consult the sections including model games. In this way, you will learn how
to grind all the seemingly equal positions that arise in this line.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "Tallinn/Parnu"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Caro-Kann Exchange"]
[Black "Theory & Plans"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "39"]
[EventDate "1998.06.19"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "EST"]
[EventCategory "15"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 {We transform into some kind of Carlsbad
structure, where knowledge of typical ideas is essential. I believe White has
very easy play in such positions.} 4. Bd3 {Restricting Bishop f5.} Nc6 (4...
Nf6 $5 5. c3 {which usually transposes.} Bg4 $5 (5... Qc7 $6 6. h3 $1 Nc6 7.
Nf3 $14) 6. Qb3 Qc7 {this is an interesting sequence of moves by black...
aiming to stop Bf4 , while still developing his Bc8 out of the pawn chain !} 7.
h3 $1 Bh5 {the only sensible way to justify black's play !} (7... Bd7 8. Nf3
Nc6 9. O-O e6 10. Qd1 $1 $14 {Typical strategy to get your queen back to e2
thus controlling the e5-square.}) 8. Ne2 $1 {this is also quite good, for
those who want to play with zero theory and typical plans!}) 5. c3 {We want to
avoid playing Nf3 right now, as to stop Bg4. Our major aim is to restrict
Black's bishop and push it into the pawn chain.} Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 $1 {pretty
much the only good move for Black!} (6... h6 7. h3 $1 $16 {If Black decides to
waste a move again, we will obviously stop Bg4 with h3 and plan Nf3 next.}) (
6... g6 $6 {very common move among various grandmasters, yet it is very risky
and possibly bad.} 7. Nf3 Bg7 (7... Bg4 8. Nbd2 Bg7 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 O-O 11.
O-O $16) 8. O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Ne5 Rc8 12. Nd3 $16) (6... e6
$2 {A very passive move, Black locks his light squared Bishop under the pawn
chain for no reason.} 7. Nd2 Be7 8. Ngf3 O-O 9. O-O $16 {White always has a
slight push in these typical positions.}) 7. Qb3 {We misplace our queen
forcing, Black to misplace his queen as well. Also, we wish to create space
for Rae1 ideas.} Qd7 $5 {This has always been the main line. Once again we
dont really need to know any theory. It's just typical plans and ideas! The
major difference between Qc8 and Qd7, is that Black might plan Bd6 in the
future.} (7... Qb6 $2 {This is wrong, as Black creates too many weaknesses.} 8.
Qxb6 axb6 9. Na3 e6 10. Nb5 Kd7 11. Ne2 $16 {White a huge advantage.}) (7... e5
$5 {pretty much the only move with concrete play !} 8. dxe5 $5 {this is the
simplest way to fight for a small advantage without much theory} (8. h3 $5 {
this is also good ..but it has a lot more theory !}) 8... Nh5 9. Be3 Nxe5 10.
Bb5+ {with concrete play, White is better at the end of the complications.} Nc6
(10... Bd7 $4 {Black won't blunder this way for sure} 11. Qxd5 $18) 11. Be2 $5
{no matter which move we will choose here, the play will be similar: fighting
against the isolated pawn !} (11. Nd2 $5 {is another intresting way to carry
out your plans} Be6 12. Qd1 Nf6 13. Ngf3 {with small edge due to IQP.}) 11...
Bxe2 (11... Nf6 12. Nd2 {planning Ngf3 to establish control of the d4 square.}
Qd7 13. Ngf3 $14 {We have a small edge due to isolated queens pawn.}) 12. Nxe2
Qd7 13. Nd2 $1 {Planning Nf3-Nd4 and attack on the d5 pawn.}) (7... Qc8 $5 8.
Nd2 {Regardless of the various move orders for both sides now, our plan is
Nd2-Ngf3-0-0 and usually Rae1! We will retreat with our queen on c2, and once
Black trades light-squared Bishops with Bh5-Bg6 we will double their pawns and
use it as a hook.} e6 (8... Bh5 {planning Bg6.} 9. Ngf3 Bg6 10. Bxg6 $1 {
Typical exchange to double the pawns.} (10. Be2 $1 {This is another way to
handle these positions, usually connected with a4-ideas.} e6 11. h3 $14) 10...
hxg6 11. O-O e6 12. h4 {with typical plans.}) 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O Bh5 (10...
O-O {Black has choosen death.} 11. Rae1 Re8 12. Ne5 Bh5 13. Re3 $1 {Planning
Qc2-Rg3 and attack!}) 11. Rae1 {Planning Ne5, Qc2, Re3 & Rg3 next.} (11. Rfe1 {
We usually get the other Rook on e1, to establish Kingside attacks.})) (7...
Na5 $6 {intresting but not worth it} 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 Qb6 {intending Bb5} (
9... e6 10. Nd2 Rc8 11. Ngf3 {with simple developement, White is much better.})
10. a4 $1 {stopping Bb5!} Nb3 (10... Qb3 11. Nd2 Qxc2 12. Bxc2 $14 {White has
a typical endgame edge.}) (10... e6 11. Nf3 Rc8 12. Nbd2 $16 Nc6 13. Qb1 Be7
14. h3 O-O 15. O-O $16 {planning Ne5 next.}) 11. Ra2 $16 {After this computer
line, White is better.}) 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 (9... Be7 $2 {Typical mistake
among amateurs, Black can't afford to ignore the e5-square.} 10. Ne5 $16 {
White has a huge advantage. We will soon castle, transfer the rook and start
attacking.}) (9... Bxf3 $5 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 $14 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1
$1 $14 {It's only about plans in such positions.}) 10. Bg3 $1 {this is equally
good with 10.Bxd6!} (10. Bxd6 $1 Qxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rae1 $1 {Again no theory,
here are some good ideas !} (12. Rfe1 $1 $14 Ne7 13. Ne5 {with chances of
kingside attack.}) 12... Bxf3 (12... Bh5 13. Ne5 {We just follow our standard
plans.}) 13. Nxf3 {with good control of the e5-square.}) 10... Bxf3 (10... O-O
11. O-O Bxg3 12. hxg3 Bh5 13. Rfe1 Bg6 14. Bb5 {Cool idea to remove the
c6-knight, to fully control the e5-square.} Qc7 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Qa3 $14 {
Planning Nb3-Nc5.}) 11. Nxf3 Bxg3 12. hxg3 a6 (12... O-O {If Black decides to
castle, he may get checkmated fast.} 13. g4 {with amazing attacking chances.})
13. Kf1 $3 {An amazing idea by GM Short! He is using both the -e and the -h
for his rooks, while the king is quite safe on f1!} Qc7 (13... h6 14. Re1 O-O
$2 15. Rh4 $1 $16 {Planning Qd1-Ne5 next, White has a typical edge.}) 14. Re1
Na5 15. Qc2 Nc4 16. Kg1 $5 {The King is even safer there.} h6 17. Bxc4 $3 {
White is winning out of nowhere!} Qxc4 18. Rxe6+ $3 fxe6 19. Qg6+ Kf8 (19...
Kd8 20. Qxg7 Re8 21. Qxf6+ $18 {with huge advantage.}) 20. Ng5 $18 {With
checkmate in a few moves.} *

