1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 g6 {can be playable
only under very specific conditions.} (6... Bg4 7. Be2 {tricky idea to trade
the Bishops.}) 7. Nd2 (7. Nf3 $5 $14 {White is already better. Because Black's
Bishop on g7 will be misplaced.}) 7... Bg7 $6 8. Ngf3 O-O 9. O-O Bf5 (9... Bg4
{We are not really afraid of this move as we can simply play} 10. h3 Bxf3 11.
Nxf3 e6 12. Re1 {with a very stable edge.}) (9... Nh5 10. Be3 f5 {is totally
pointless as we can respond with} 11. Nb3 f4 12. Bd2 {when Black has no
threats.}) (9... Ne8 {planning f6-e5, but we have something prepared as well!}
10. h3 f6 11. c4 {Typical way to meet f6-e5 ideas.} dxc4 12. Bxc4+ {Black has
many weakness.}) 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Ne1 $1 {the Knight looks great on d3 in
such positions!} (11. Ne5 {is also possible, although we don't need to trade
the Knights.}) 11... e6 12. Nd3 Kh8 (12... Ne4 {doesn't make much sense.} 13.
f3 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 {is simply much better for White.}) 13. Re1 Rg8 (13... Ne4 14.
Nf1 (14. f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2) 14... Rc8 15. f3 Nd6 (15... Nf6 16. h3 a6 17. g4
fxg4 18. hxg4 Qd7 19. Ng3 b6 20. Rc1 a5 21. Rc2 b5 22. Nc5 (22. Rh2)) 16. Ng3)
14. Nf1 (14. Re3 $1 Bf8 15. Rg3 (15. Rh3)) 14... b6 15. Ng3 a5 16. a4 $1 Ra7
17. Qb3 Nd7 18. Qb5 Ncb8 19. Nh5 Qh4 20. Nxg7 Rxg7 21. Bxb8 Nxb8 22. Qxb6 Nc6
23. Qxc6 f4 24. Ne5 Qg5 25. g3 fxg3 26. hxg3 h5 27. Kg2 h4 28. Rh1 f5 29. Qe8+
Kh7 30. Nf3 1-0

