{The ratings of the players don't matter at all. Rather, I would look if the
game is instructive or not.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. c3 e6
6. Bf4 {Black's main problem is his terrible Bishop on c8.} (6. Nf3 {is
equally good.} Bd6 7. Bg5) 6... Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O a6 (9... O-O
{White has two main ideas to consider: Nbd2 or Re1 & Qe2. It is better to
start with controlling the e5 square first.} 10. Re1 (10. Nbd2 {You can't
afford to waste a move like this. It is essential to first control the center.}
e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Nf3 Qc7 14. h3 {with equal chances.}) 10...
b6 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Ne5 Ne7 13. f4 {White has amazing attacking possibilites,
it is a good London for White. Always, remmember to keep the control of the e4
square.}) 10. a4 {is not necessary. Usually, when Black has an Bishop closed
under the pawn chain, his minority is not serious at all.} (10. Nbd2 b5 11. b4
{Leading to a winning position immediately.}) 10... O-O 11. Re1 Ne7 12. Ne5 Bd7
13. Qe2 Ng6 14. g3 Bc6 15. Nd2 Ne7 16. Qf3 (16. f4 {would have been better.})
16... b5 17. a5 Rab8 18. b4 Nd7 19. Qg4 Rbc8 20. Nb3 Rfe8 21. Re3 Ng6 22. Rae1
Ngxe5 23. dxe5 Qe7 24. Nd4 Bb7 25. f4 h6 26. h4 Kh8 27. f5 Rg8 28. fxe6 fxe6
29. Rf3 Nf8 30. Rxf8 Rgxf8 31. Qg6 Kg8 32. Qh7+ 1-0

