[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "French Exchange"]
[Black "4.Bf4 Theory"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C01"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "25"]
[EventDate "2020.04.19"]

{[%evp 0,25,20,16,53,38,28,13,13,-11,-3,-37,-19,-19,-23,-5,-7,-59,-27,-40,-16,
-26,-10,-25,-16,-32,-4,6]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Bf4 $5 {A
playable and easy to learn line! Our plan is Bf4-Nc3-Qd2 and 0-0-0 followed by
f3-g4 or h4-h5-h6 etc with good attacking chances. However, at any moment if
we exchange the dark square bishops, our plan can change right away, playing
for the better endgame! We want to avoid the tons of theory of the French
defense of course. Please do not forget that if the position demands it, we
may go for short castling as well.} Bd6 (4... Nf6 {Black can play various
moves of course! We don't need much theory, you should only be able to decide
if you will castle long or short. Which depends also on Black's moves!} 5. Nc3
Bb4 {now, we need to go for short castling!} (5... c5 $2 {this is a bad move
which many people will play !} 6. Nb5 $3 $14 {and after the forced 6...Na6,
Black cannot get rid of our Nb5 with an a6 move !}) (5... Bd6 6. Qd2 {typical
reaction.} O-O 7. O-O-O Nc6 8. f3 $36 {Planning g4-g5-h4 and so on.}) 6. Bd3
O-O 7. Nge2 $1 {with usual developing plans. Black will have to either capture
on c3 or retreat with Bd6 resulting into similar with a tempo up for us.}) (
4... Nc6 5. Nc3 $5 {We just follow our basic instincts.} Nf6 6. Qd2 Bb4 7. f3
O-O 8. O-O-O Re8 9. g4 $132 {plan to launch a kingside attack}) (4... c5 $2 {
is a huge mistake as it allows} 5. Nc3 $1 Nf6 6. Nb5 {Now, Black has to solve
some huge problems.}) 5. Qd2 $1 {Supporting the f4 Bishop, we might also aim
for a better endgame if the position demands it.} Ne7 (5... Qe7+ $6 {tricky
idea but against basic principles} 6. Ne2 Bxf4 7. Qxf4 Qb4+ $2 8. Nbc3 Qxb2 {
Black won a pawn but that's too greddy on his part. Concrete things favor
White as you will see in the following line} 9. Rb1 $3 Qxc2 10. Rc1 $3 Qf5 11.
Qxf5 Bxf5 12. Nxd5 Na6 13. Nef4 $3 $16 Rc8 14. Bxa6 bxa6 15. Kd2 $16 {White
has a huge advantage.}) 6. Nc3 {And now, Here are some sample lines, in all
the cases white has an easy game with natural moves! Note: We can castle long
or castle short or go for a queen trade in the famous endgame without the
dark-square bishops! It all depends on the position.} O-O (6... Bxf4 7. Qxf4 {
After trading the dark-squared Bishops, we would very much like to reach an
endgame.} c6 (7... Qd6 $2 {horrible!} 8. Qxd6 $1 cxd6 9. Bd3 Nbc6 10. Nge2 {
White has a huge advantage.}) 8. Bd3 Ng6 9. Qe3+ $16 (9. Bxg6 $1 hxg6 10. O-O-O
O-O 11. h4 $16 {is a good alternative if you wish to keep queens on the board.}
) 9... Qe7 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. Nce2 {Planning c3 to stabilize the position. We
have a very slight edge. Our new plans include f3-Kf2-Bxg6 & sometimes fixing
the structure with h4.}) 7. O-O-O {A common idea is h4-h5-h6 or f3-g4-h4 etc.}
Nbc6 (7... Ng6 {Forcing us to trade the Bishops, which we anyway wanted to do}
8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. h4 $16 {Planning h5-h6 next.}) 8. f3 $5 Be6 (8... Ng6 9. Bxd6
Qxd6 10. h4 $16 Qf4 11. h5 {We don't shy away to trade the queens. White has
better chances in the seemingly equal endgame.}) 9. Nge2 a6 10. h4 $16 (10. g4
b5 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Qf4 {is also possible if you are an endgame geek.}) 10...
b5 11. Bxd6 $1 (11. Kb1 $2 {This is wasting an essential tempo of the endgame,
as we anyway aiming for the same.} Na5 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Qf4 Nc4 14. Qxd6 Nxd6
{And now we can see Kb1 was a waste of time.}) 11... Qxd6 12. Qf4 $1 Qxf4+ (
12... Qd7 {If Black tries to run away from trading the queens, he is simply
lacking initiative in the attack.} 13. h5 h6 14. g4 {White is simply much
faster in the attack.}) 13. Nxf4 $16 {White is better in such types of
endgames as well. Black's light-squared Bishop is very passive.} *

