{[%evp 0,21,16,23,46,28,28,13,13,3,20,-3,-4,-10,-16,-34,-11,-7,15,26,9,0,10,10]
} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 $5 {this is another good and simple
line for White. We have many ways to play such a position and we will try to
avoid theory as much as possible!} Nc6 (4... Bf5 $6 5. Bd3 $3 {This is a
surprisingly good move here! Although we exchange our good bishop , we get
quick development chances.} Bxd3 6. Qxd3 c6 (6... Nc6 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nc3 $3 Nge7
9. Ne2 O-O 10. Bf4 $14) 7. Qe2+ $3 {What an amazing move by the computer, Do
remember this amazing idea. Black has big problems with his king now because
if he plays Be7 or Ne7 , its not easy to castle, while if he plays Qe7 we go
Be3! and he cannot develop. Of course ts idea works only when there is a Bf8
and Ng8 not with the bishop already on d6} Be7 (7... Qe7 8. Be3 $1 $14 (8.
Qxe7+ $4 {Doesn't make any sense. Black simply secures equality.} Nxe7 $15 {
Planning f6-Kf7 next, Black has achieved a position we always wanted to have.})
) 8. O-O Nf6 9. Re1 $16 {Black somehow can't castle now.}) (4... Nf6 $1 {
A simple and good move} 5. Bd3 {our plan is to play Bd3- 0-0 , Bg5 ..and
Nbd2-c3-Qc2 this gives us easy play and possibly a small advantage.} Bd6 (5...
Be7 {is also possible.} 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 c6 8. Bf4 $14 {White got a nice
diagonal and he doesn't mind trading the DSB.}) 6. O-O O-O 7. Bg5 {With equal
chances for both sides.}) (4... Bg4 $6 {a very common inaccurracy.} 5. h3 Bh5
6. Qe2+ $3 Qe7 7. Be3 $1 {Typical roadblock strategy to castle long quickly.})
(4... c5 $2 {Once again, a quick c5 is a very common mistake.} 5. Bb5+ Nc6 6.
O-O Bd6 7. c4 $3 $16 {With clear advantage as per computer.}) (4... Bd6 5. Bd3
{This time we cannot get Bf4, so we simply follow our basic piece placements.}
(5. c4 $5 $14 {is another popular line.}) 5... Ne7 6. O-O Bg4 7. Re1 Nbc6 (7...
O-O $4 {is a huge blunder!} 8. Bxh7+ {with a clear advantage for White.}) 8. c3
Qd7 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nbd2 Bg6 11. Bf1 $16 {Preserving the Bishop for the funky
business on the queenside.}) (4... c6 {a bit passive ..we continue with normal
moves} 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. O-O Be7 7. h3 $5 O-O 8. Bf4 $14) 5. Bf4 $5 Bd6 (5... Nf6
6. c3 Be7 (6... Bd6 {We always like to trade dark squared Bishops.} 7. Bxd6
Qxd6 8. Bd3 $1 {stopping Bf5 ideas is very imp as well.} O-O 9. O-O Bg4 10.
Nbd2 Rfe8 11. h3 Bh5 12. Qb3 $14 {with a slight push.}) 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O $14)
6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. c3 {With our Knight already developed on f3, we won't play Nc3
as well.} Nge7 (7... Bg4 8. Nbd2 {We just follow our standard piece placements.
} Nf6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Rfe8 11. h3 Bd7 12. Qc2 g6 13. b4 $14 {planning
a4-a5-a6. We just want to exploit, Black's badly placed Knight on c6.}) 8. Bd3
$1 {The bishop is btter placed on d3!} Bf5 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 $14 (10. Bxf5 {
is playable as well.} Nxf5 11. Nbd2 $14 Rfe8 12. Qb3 b6 13. Rfe1 {1-0 (47)
Kamsky,G-Grischuk,A/chess.com INT 2022/[,ÃéÜííçò]}) 10... Rfe8 11. Na3
$14 {This simplified position is in fact very unpleasant for Black! The Knight
stands very badly placed on c6, making d5 and b7 potential weaknesses against
sudden attacks!} *

