1. e4 {An interesting example of endgame play in exchange french.} e6 2. d4 d5
3. exd5 exd5 4. Bf4 Bd6 5. Bxd6 $5 {Our choice is 5.Qd2 but once again, theory
doesn't matter.} Qxd6 6. c3 {is slightly innacurate.} (6. Nc3 $5 {would have
been choice.}) 6... c6 7. Bd3 Nf6 (7... Ne7 8. Qc2 {Intending to create some
weaknesses.} g6 9. Ne2 Bf5 10. O-O Bxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. Nd2 Nd7 13. Ng3 {
with slight chances for White.}) 8. Qe2+ Qe6 $2 (8... Be6 {Black should
definetely try not trade the queens.}) 9. Qxe6+ Bxe6 10. Nf3 $2 {The Knight
does not belong there!} (10. Ne2 $16 {This is a better move with usual plans,
of f3-Kf2-Nd2.} Nbd7 11. f3 O-O 12. Nd2 Rfe8 13. Kf2 Nf8 14. h4 {I dislike to
give Black any chance with g4-Bxg4 tricks instead. If you are not sure about
g4, you don't owe it to anyone. Simply ignore it.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12.
O-O Rfe8 13. Rfe1 Bg4 14. Rxe8+ Rxe8 15. Re1 Rxe1+ (15... Bxf3 {Black should
try to trade the LSB instead.} 16. Nxf3 Rxe1+ 17. Nxe1 g6 {with equal chances.}
) 16. Nxe1 Bh5 17. f3 Kf8 18. Kf2 Ke7 19. Nc2 Bg6 20. Ke3 (20. Bxg6 {Creating
a new weakness!} hxg6 21. h4 Ne8 22. Nb3 b6 23. Nc1 {with a microscopic edge
for White.}) 20... Bxd3 21. Kxd3 Ne8 22. Ne3 Nd6 23. b3 Ke6 24. Ndf1 Nf5 25.
Nxf5 Kxf5 26. g3 Ke6 27. Ne3 g6 28. Ng2 Kd6 29. Ke3 Ke6 30. Nf4+ Kd6 31. Nd3
1/2-1/2

