[PlyCount "13"]
[EventType "swiss (blitz)"]

1. e4 Nc6 {Nimzovich Defence} (1... b6 {Owen Defence} 2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 e6 4.
Nf3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {White has a strong pawn center and a nice advantage.}) (1... a6
{Saint George Defence} 2. d4 b5 3. Nf3 Bb7 4. Bd3 e6 5. O-O c5 6. c3 Nf6 7. Re1
$16 {White has a strong pawn center and a nice advantage. For instance} d5 8.
e5 Ne4 9. Nbd2 Nxd2 10. Bxd2 Be7 11. Rc1 Nd7 12. a3 O-O 13. Qc2 $5 (13. h4 $5
Bxh4 14. Nxh4 (14. g3 Be7 15. Kg2 $16) 14... Qxh4 15. Re3 $18 {[%cal Ye3h3]})
13... g6 (13... h6 14. Qd1 {(to play Bb1 and Qc2)} Re8 15. Bb1 Bf8 16. Qc2 g6
17. h4 $18) 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Qd2 $18) 2. Nf3 $1 {The simplest answer.} (2. d4 d5
{leads to unnecessary complications!}) 2... d6 (2... e5 $1 {The only good move
for Black! With a transposition to 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6.}) (2... d5 {This leads
to a very bad version of the Scandinavian for Black!} 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5
5. Bb5 $1 Bd7 6. d4 $16 (6. O-O $16)) 3. d4 {Now we have a very good version
of the Pirc.} Nf6 (3... Bg4 4. d5 $1 Ne5 (4... Nb8 5. h3 $16) 5. Nxe5 $1 Bxd1
6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 a6 8. c7+ $16) (3... e5 4. Bb5 $1 $14 {/+/- leads to the
Steinitz Defence of the Ruy Lopez.}) 4. Nc3 e5 5. Bb5 $1 exd4 6. Nxd4 (6. Qxd4
$5 Bd7 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Bg5 Be7 9. O-O-O O-O 10. Rhe1 $14) 6... Bd7 7. O-O $14 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.01.08"]
[Round "?"]
[White "PART 2: PIRC- & MODERN DEFENC"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "35"]
[EventType "swiss (blitz)"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {Systems with ...d6, ...g6, and ...Nf6 are called the Pirc
Defence, whereas systems without an early ...Nf6 are called the Modern Defence.
} (2... g6 {Our plans work also perfectly against the Modern Defence. Against
systems with the knight still on g8 we will mainly go for short castling.} 3.
Nc3 Bg7 4. Be3 a6 5. Qd2 {Make sure to study the model games to understand the
typical plans!} b5 6. f3 Bb7 7. a4 $14 {A sample variation:} (7. Nh3 $14) 7...
b4 8. Nd1 a5 9. Nh3 e6 10. Be2 Nd7 11. O-O Ne7 12. Ndf2 c5 13. c3 $16) 3. Nc3
g6 (3... e5 4. Nf3 {Now we have transposed to the Philidor Defence. A possible
line:} Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6 8. h3 Qc7 9. Re1 b6 10. Be3 Bb7 11.
Ba2 $16 {Next, we would like to play Nh4, but have to check wether ...Nxe4
works!}) 4. f3 {This line of the Pirc Defence is very easy to learn !!  White
will play Be3-f3-Qd2 and when Black commits the very common but big mistake of
castling short too early, we play Bh6 and gain a very strong attack with h4-h5
!! If Black postpones ...0-0 (which is the correct thing to do!) and plays
moves on the queenside like a6-b5-Bb7-Nd7 etc., we go for short castling !!}
Bg7 5. Be3 O-O $2 (5... c6 6. Qd2 Nbd7 (6... O-O $2 7. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Ye3h6,
Yh2h4,Yh4h5]}) 7. Nge2 $1 {Here we go for short castling! Prepared by either
Nge2 or Nh3.} (7. O-O-O $6 b5 $1 $132 8. e5 $140 b4 $1 9. Nce2 Nd5) (7. Nh3 $5
b5 8. Be2 Bb7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nf2 $14 (10. a4 $14)) 7... b5 8. Ng3 Bb7 9. Be2 $1
(9. a4 $1 b4 10. Nd1 c5 11. c3 a5 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O e5 14. Nf2) 9... O-O 10.
h4 $5 $14 {Since Black has castled and we haven't, playing on the kingside
becomes again possible.} (10. O-O $14) 10... h5 11. Bh6 $14) 6. Qd2 $16 {
White has a strong attack - here are some sample lines:} c6 (6... Nbd7 7. O-O-O
e5 8. dxe5 (8. g4 $16) (8. h4 h5 9. Be2 $1 $16 a6 10. g4) 8... Nxe5 9. Bh6 $16)
(6... e5 7. O-O-O $1 ({or just} 7. Nge2 $1 {followed by 0-0-0.}) 7... exd4 (
7... Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. g4 $16 (9. Bh6 $16)) 8. Bxd4 Nc6 9. Be3 {Black has won a
tempo with ...Nc6, but is still in a bad position as he cannot generate any
counterplay in the center.} Re8 10. Bh6 Bh8 11. Nge2 Ne5 12. Nf4 $16 {[%cal
Yh2h4]}) (6... Re8 7. Bh6 Bh8 8. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Yh2h4,Yh4h5]}) 7. O-O-O (7.
Bh6 $5 e5 (7... b5 {--> see model game Andreikin-Bryakin.}) 8. Bxg7 (8. Nge2
Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Qh4+) 8... Kxg7 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. g4 $16) 7... Nbd7 (7... e5) 8.
Bh6 $1 {[%cal Yh2h4,Yh4h5] The alternatives are also good, but it makes sense
to prevent Black from blocking our h-pawn - we will continue with h4-h5.} (8.
h4 h5) (8. g4 b5 9. h4 h5) 8... b5 (8... e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. h4 Re8 11. g4 $16
Bxh6 12. Qxh6 Qe7 13. h5 (13. Nh3 Qf8 14. Qe3 Qc5 15. Qg5 $16) 13... Nf8 14.
Nh3) 9. h4 Qa5 10. Kb1 b4 11. Nce2 Nb6 12. Nc1 $1 $18 {REMEMBER THIS TYPICAL
PLAN OF DEFENCE WITH Kb1-Nc1 !!} Bd7 13. h5 Nxh5 14. g4 Nf6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16.
Qh6+ Kg8 17. Nb3 Qa4 18. e5 *

