1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 $1 (3. Nc3 $5 {Not my main suggestion, but one line
with very little theory.} Nxc3 (3... e6 4. Ne4 $5) 4. bxc3 {Most players will
play} d6 {but White can defend e5 very well, e.g.} (4... d5 $1 $11 {ist best.})
5. f4 Nc6 (5... g6 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 $14) 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. d4 $14) 3...
d6 4. Nf3 $1 {The simplest continuation, that leads to at least a slightly
better position in all cases! WHAT WILL BE OUR NEXT MOVE, DEPENDS ON WHAT
VARIATION BLACK WILL PLAY!} dxe5 $1 {That's the most common move!} (4... Bg4 $1
5. Be2 $1 {SOS !! A VERY IMPORTANT RULE OF THUMB IN THIS PARTICULAR LINE WITH
4...Bg4: We should be careful to NOT end up with a weak pawn on e5! NOW, BLACK
WOULD VERY MUCH LIKE TO TAKE ON e5, when we would be forced to take back with
the pawn, and play e6-Nd7. We do not allow it! Generally, we want to take back
on e5 with the knight!} e6 (5... dxe5 6. Nxe5 $1 {No weak pawn on e5 for us!
It is also good to exchange the light-squared bishops as this gives a lot of
freedom to our queen.} Bxe2 7. Qxe2 c6 (7... Nd7 8. O-O $16) 8. O-O e6 9. c4
Nf6 10. Rd1 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bf4 Nbd7 13. Rd3 $1) (5... c6 6. c4 Nb6 7. Ng5
$5 Bxe2 8. Qxe2 dxe5 9. dxe5 h6 10. Nf3 $16 {We ended up with a pawn on e5,
but it is well supported and gives White a big space advantage.}) 6. O-O dxe5 (
6... Bxf3 $2 {INTENDING TO FORCE US TO PUT A PAWN ON e5. This doesn't work
well for Black:} 7. Bxf3 dxe5 8. c4 $1 $18 (8. dxe5 $6 c6 9. Nd2 Nd7 $132 {
This is exactly the kind of position we would like to avoid! Black has
counterplay against our pawn on e5 and an extra knight!})) (6... Nd7 7. c4 N5b6
8. exd6 cxd6 9. b3 $16) (6... Be7 7. h3 Bh5 8. c4 Nb6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 $16)
7. Nxe5 Bxe2 8. Qxe2 Nd7 9. c4 N5f6 10. Nc3 Be7 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Rad1 c6 13. Rd3
Qa5 14. Rfd1 $16 {Black is under pressure and cannot free himself.} Nxe5 $2 15.
dxe5 Ne8 16. Rd7 $18) (4... Nc6 $6 5. c4 Nb6 6. e6 $3 $16 fxe6 {White has very
good compensation, e.g.} (6... Bxe6 $4 7. d5 $18) 7. Be3 e5 8. d5 Nd4 9. Nxd4 (
9. Nc3 $16) 9... exd4 10. Qxd4 e5 11. Qd2 $16) (4... g6 5. Bc4 c6 (5... Nb6 6.
Bb3 Bg7 (6... d5 7. Nh4 $5 {Stopping both ...Bg4 and ...Bf5.} Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9.
f4 $16) 7. Ng5 e6 (7... O-O 8. e6 $1 $16) 8. Qf3 Qe7 9. Ne4 $1 $16 {[%cal
Yc1g5] see model game Pichot-Kourkoulos.}) 6. exd6 Qxd6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O
9. Nbd2 $16 {White has a nice advantage - Black is solid but passive.} (9. Bg5
$16)) 5. Nxe5 Nd7 (5... g6 6. Be2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. c4 Nb6 9. f4 N8d7 10. Nc3)
(5... c6 6. Bc4 (6. Be2 g6 (6... Nd7 7. Nf3 $16) 7. O-O Bg7 8. c4 Nc7 9. f4 $14
) 6... Nd7 7. Nf3 $14) (5... Bf5 $2 6. Bd3 $1 (6. Qf3 e6 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 8. g4 Qf6
9. gxf5 Qxf5 10. Nd2 $16) 6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Nd7 8. Qb3 Nxe5 9. dxe5 $16 Nb6 10.
e6) 6. Nf3 $3 (6. Nxf7 $5 Kxf7 7. Qh5+ Ke6 8. c4 N5f6 9. d5+ Kd6) 6... N7f6 7.
Be2 $1 (7. c4 $1 Nb6 8. Nc3 Bg4 9. Be2) 7... Bg4 8. O-O e6 9. Ne5 Bxe2 10. Qxe2
c6 11. c4 Nb6 12. Rd1 Be7 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Bf4 Re8 15. Rd3 $3 Nbd7 16. Rad1 $16
*

