1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 (2... Nf6 $5 3. Bb5+ $5 {A clever way to destroy Black's
coordination!} Bd7 (3... Nbd7 4. d4 Nxd5 5. Nf3 c6 6. Be2 $14 (6. Bd3 $14) 6...
N7f6 7. c4 $16) 4. Be2 $1 Nxd5 5. d4 Bf5 6. a3 $1 e6 7. c4 Nb6 (7... Nf6 8. Nc3
Be7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O (10. Nh4 $14) 10... Nbd7 11. Nh4 $16 (11. Be3 $14)) 8.
Nc3 Be7 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. O-O O-O 11. Be3 Bf6 (11... Bg4 12. b3 Bf6 13. Ne4 $16
Bxf3 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Bxf3) 12. b4 Bg4 13. Ne4 Bxf3 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Bxf3
Nxc4 16. Rc1 Nxe3 17. fxe3 $16 Qg5 18. Qb3) 3. Nc3 Qa5 {This has always been
the main line. Now, I suggest a very simple system, avoiding lots of theory
and complications, right in the spirit of our repertoire with 1.e4: The
Bc4-d3-system! We play Bc4, d3, followed by either Qe2-Nf3, or the even
simpler Nge2 ! We get a small plus in all cases without much trouble!} (3...
Qd6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nb5 $5 {This is a very good practical choice! We do not allow
our opponent to show his knowledge in the mainline!} Qd8 (5... Qb6 6. Nf3 Bg4 (
6... c6 7. Na3 $1 Bg4 8. Be2 e6 9. Nc4 Qc7 10. Nce5 $14) (6... a6 7. Na3 $3 {
This is the key move of the whole system - Na3 and then Nc4 !!} Be6 8. c3 c5 9.
Nc4 $16 Bxc4 10. Bxc4 cxd4 11. Qxd4 $16) (6... Bf5 7. c4 $5 (7. Na3 $5 c6 8.
Nc4 Qc7 9. Nce5 $14 (9. Bd3 $14) (9. g3 $1 $14)) 7... c6 8. Nc3 $14 (8. c5 $14)
) 7. Na3 $1 (7. Be2 $4 Bxf3 $17) 7... Nbd7 8. Be2 e6 9. Nc4 Qc6 10. Qd3 (10.
Ne3) 10... Bf5 11. Qb3 $14) 6. c4 $1 a6 (6... Bg4 7. Be2 Bxe2 8. Nxe2 c6 9.
Nbc3 e6 10. O-O $14) (6... e6 7. Nf3 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 a6 10. Nc3 O-O
11. Be2 $14) 7. Nc3 Bf5 (7... c5 8. d5 $14) 8. Nf3 e6 9. Bd3 $14 (9. Be3 $14) (
9. Be2 $16)) (3... Qd8 $6 {This is a passive move, White is much better here.
But a nice improvement over the common theory should be mentioned - see 8.g4!}
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 $1 Bg4 (5... c6 6. Ne5 $14 Nbd7 7. Bd3 $16 (7. Qf3 $16)) (5...
g6 6. Bc4 $14) 6. h3 $1 Bxf3 (6... Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 $16) 7. Qxf3 c6 8. g4
$1 {A strong improvement!! This is much better than the common 8.Be3.} Qxd4 (
8... e6 9. g5 Nd5 10. Bd2 $5 $16 (10. Ne4 $3 $16 Nb4 11. Qe2 $3 $16 Qxd4 12. c3
Qd5 13. a3 $3 N4a6 14. b4 $16 Nd7 15. Bg2 $16 {with tremendous compensation
for the pawn! The black king has nowhere to hide!}) 10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 $5 (11.
bxc3 $5 Qd5 12. Qxd5 cxd5 13. Rb1 b6 14. c4 $16)) 9. Be3 Qb4 10. O-O-O $16 e6
11. g5 $1 (11. Bd4 $1 $16) 11... Nd5 12. Bd4 $16 (12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. c4 $16)
12... Be7 13. h4 $16 O-O 14. Ne4 $16 (14. Bd3 $16 {with a powerful attack!}))
4. Bc4 {Now, we will look at some sample lines:} Nf6 5. d3 $1 Bg4 (5... c6 6.
Qe2 (6. Nge2 $14 {This is also simple and good - just castle short and get a
small plus without any trouble.} Bf5 7. O-O e6 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. Bd2 $14 (9. f4 $14
) 9... Qc7 10. f4 $16) 6... Bg4 (6... Bf5 7. Bd2 e6 8. h3 Bb4 9. g4 Bg6 10. f4
O-O 11. Nf3 $14) 7. f3 $1 Bf5 8. Bd2 Qc7 9. g4 Bd7 (9... Bg6 10. f4 $18) 10. d4
$16 (10. g5 $16)) (5... Bf5 6. Bd2 (6. Nge2 $5 e6 7. O-O c6 (7... Bd6 8. Bd2
Qb6 9. Na4 Qc6 10. Nd4 $3 $18) 8. Ng3 (8. Nd4 $5) 8... Bg6 9. Bd2 (9. f4) 9...
Qc7 10. f4 $14) 6... c6 7. Qe2 $14 Qc7 8. h3 e6 9. g4 Bg6 10. f4 $14) (5... e6
6. Nf3 {Now we no longer have to fear ...Bg4.}) 6. Nge2 $1 c6 (6... Nc6 $5 7.
O-O e6 8. h3 Bxe2 (8... Bh5 9. Bb5 $16) 9. Nxe2 $1 Bd6 10. c3 O-O 11. d4 $14 (
11. a4 $14)) 7. O-O e6 8. h3 Bh5 (8... Bxe2 9. Qxe2 $14) 9. Qe1 $5 Bg6 10. Nf4
$14 *

